n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Billy Knott\n| image               = Billy Knott.jpg\n| caption             = Knott in 2011.\n| fullname            = Billy Steven Knott<ref>{{Cite web |title=List of Players under Written Contract Registered Between 01/02/2013 and 28/02/2013 |url=http://www.thefa.com/football-rules-governance/more/~/media/774E2ECF9B3E4EE3A300FD51BF8EA6C1.ashx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607170138/http://www.thefa.com/football-rules-governance/more/~/media/774E2ECF9B3E4EE3A300FD51BF8EA6C1.ashx |url-status=dead |archivedate=7 June 2013 |publisher=The Football Association |format=PDF |accessdate=12 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1992|11|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Canvey Island]], England\n| height              = {{height|m=1.73}}<ref>{{cite web |title=FootballSquads - Port Vale - 2013/14 |url=http://www.footballsquads.co.uk/eng/2013-2014/flone/portv.htm |website=www.footballsquads.co.uk |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref>\n| position            = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub         = [[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]]\n| clubnumber          = \n| youthyears1         =          | youthclubs1 = [[Concord Rangers F.C.|Concord Rangers]]\n| youthyears2         = 2003\u20132007| youthclubs2 = [[West Ham United F.C. Reserves and Academy|West Ham United]]\n| youthyears3         = 2007\u20132010| youthclubs3 = [[Chelsea F.C. Reserves and Academy|Chelsea]]\n| youthyears4         = 2010\u20132011| youthclubs4 = [[Sunderland A.F.C. Reserves and Academy|Sunderland]]\n| years1              = 2011\u20132014| clubs1 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]                     | caps1 =  1| goals1 = 0\n| years2              = 2012     | clubs2 = \u2192 [[AFC Wimbledon]] (loan)                           | caps2 = 20| goals2 = 3\n| years3              = 2012\u20132013| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Woking F.C.|Woking]] (loan)                      | caps3 = 20| goals3 = 8\n| years4              = 2013\u20132014| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] (loan)| caps4 = 17| goals4 = 1\n| years5              = 2014     | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] (loan)                | caps5 = 17| goals5 = 2\n| years6              = 2014\u20132016| clubs6 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]               | caps6 = 64| goals6 = 3\n| years7              = 2016\u20132017| clubs7 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]                       | caps7 = 17| goals7 = 1\n| years8              = 2017     | clubs8 = \u2192 [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] (loan)          | caps8 = 13| goals8 = 1\n| years9              = 2017\u20132018| clubs9 = [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]]                   | caps9 = 14| goals9 = 1\n| years10             = 2018     | clubs10 = \u2192 [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] (loan)               | caps10=  4| goals10= 0\n| years11             = 2018\u20132019| clubs11 = [[Concord Rangers F.C.|Concord Rangers]]            | caps11= 11| goals11= 1\n| years12             = 2019\u2013    | clubs12 = [[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]]            | caps12= 26| goals12= 0\n| nationalyears1      = 2007     | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]| nationalcaps1 = 1| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2      = 2008     | nationalteam2 = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]| nationalcaps2 = 6| nationalgoals2 = 1\n| nationalyears3      = 2011     | nationalteam3 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]]| nationalcaps3 = 4| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| club-update         = 20:00, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Billy Steven Knott''' (born 28 November 1992) is an English [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[National League South]] club [[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]].\n\nHe has represented England at [[England national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]] and [[England national under-20 football team|under-20]] level. He joined [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] after being released from the [[Chelsea F.C. Reserves and Academy|Chelsea Academy]] in 2011. He played one game for the club, and spent periods on loan at [[AFC Wimbledon]], [[Woking F.C.|Woking]], [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]], and [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]]. He joined [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in May 2014, and remained with the club for two seasons, before he joined Gillingham in June 2016. He joined [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] on loan in January 2017, and joined the club permanently after he helped Lincoln to the 2016\u201317 [[National League (division)|National League]] title. He joined [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] on loan in January 2018, before transferring to [[Concord Rangers F.C.|Concord Rangers]] in June 2018. He switched to Chelmsford City in March 2019.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Sunderland===\nKnott joined the [[West Ham United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Academy]] at [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] at the age of ten, before moving with his family to [[Spain]] after his mother was diagnosed with [[lupus]].<ref name=\"interv\">{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Matthew |title=Interview: Billy Knott |url=https://thesetpieces.com/interviews/interview-billy-knott/ |accessdate=16 March 2019 |work=The Set Pieces |date=23 January 2015}}</ref> In Spain, West Ham arranged for a trial with [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]], but after the family returned to London he elected to join the [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] [[Chelsea F.C. Reserves and Academy|Academy]] rather than rejoin West Ham.<ref name=\"interv\"/> He was signed by [[Premier League]] club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] after he was released by Chelsea in the [[2010\u201311 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2010\u201311]] season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Billy Knott |url=http://www.safc.com/page/PlayerProfiles/0,,10281~55137,00.html |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C |accessdate=3 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110901231816/http://www.safc.com/page/PlayerProfiles/0%2C%2C10281~55137%2C00.html |archivedate=1 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He had been dismissed from the Chelsea Academy and forced to sign a [[Non-disclosure agreement|confidentiality agreement]] after a \"[[smoke grenade]] incident\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilson|first1=Scott|title=Billy hoping to tie Sunderland in Knotts|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/11792655.Billy_hoping_to_tie_Sunderland_in_Knotts/|accessdate=24 October 2016|work=The Northern Echo|date=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nKnott joined [[Terry Brown (football manager)|Terry Brown]]'s [[EFL League Two|League Two]] side [[AFC Wimbledon]] on loan on 11 January 2012,<ref>{{cite news|title=Wimbledon tie up Knott on loan|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12691/7424684/Wimbledon-tie-up-Knott-on-loan|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[Sky Sports]]|date=12 January 2012}}</ref> and made his debut in a 2\u20131 win against [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] three days later.<ref>{{cite news|title=Port Vale 1 - 2 AFC Wimbledon|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/16453168.stm|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=14 January 2012}}</ref> He scored his first goal in professional football at [[Kingsmeadow]] in a 2\u20131 win over [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] on 24 January.<ref>{{cite news|title=AFC Wimbledon 2 - 1 Macclesfield|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16589133|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=24 January 2012}}</ref> The 19-year-old received the \"Dons\" Young Player of the Year award, despite only playing half the [[2011\u201312 AFC Wimbledon season|2011\u201312]] season, having scored three goals in twenty appearances.<ref>{{cite web|title=Award for youngster Knott|url=http://www.safc.premiumtv.co.uk/news/20120508/award-for-youngster-knott_2256213_2763549|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130707053332/http://www.safc.premiumtv.co.uk/news/20120508/award-for-youngster-knott_2256213_2763549|url-status=dead|archivedate=7 July 2013|publisher=SAFC.com|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 October 2012, Knott joined [[National League (division)|Conference Premier]] side [[Woking F.C.|Woking]] on a one-month loan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sunderland midfielder Billy Knott loaned to Woking|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19885515|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=9 October 2012}}</ref> He made his debut at [[Kingfield Stadium]] in a 2\u20131 win over [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] the following day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Woking 2 - 1 Cambridge|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19796555|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=9 October 2012}}</ref> His first goals came for [[Garry Hill]]'s \"Cardinals\" came against [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] on 1 January 2013, when he scored twice in a 3\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite news|title=Woking 3 - 1 Luton|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20841252|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=1 January 2013}}</ref> He scored another two goals on 2 February, in a 2\u20131 win over [[Hyde United F.C.|Hyde]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Woking 2 - 1 Hyde|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21209158|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=2 February 2013}}</ref> He was awarded the club's Goal of the Season award for his curled effort against Hyde, which was also nominated for the Conference's Goal of the Season competition.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shaw|first=Nick|title=Goal of the Season - The Result|url=http://www.wokingfc.co.uk/news/article/4048/goal-of-the-season-the-result/|work=wokingfc.co.uk|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> Knott scored eight goals in twenty league games, and returned to the [[Stadium of Light]], at the end of Woking's season, after a 2\u20131 defeat to [[Tamworth F.C.|Tamworth]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamworth 2 - 1 Woking|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22133484|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=20 April 2013}}</ref> Manager [[Paolo Di Canio]] handed him his Sunderland debut on 19 May 2013, the last day of the [[2012\u201313 Premier League]] season, coming on as a substitute in a 1\u20130 defeat to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[White Hart Lane]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McNulty|first=Phil|title=Tottenham 2 - 1 Sunderland|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22499089|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=19 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nKnott joined League Two side [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] on a one-month youth loan deal on 20 August 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Knott links up with Wycombe|url=http://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2013/august/knott-heads-to-wycombe|publisher=Sunderland AFC|accessdate=20 August 2013|date=20 August 2013}}</ref> He made his Wycombe debut four days later in a 2\u20132 draw with local-rivals [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]], and manager [[Gareth Ainsworth]] stated that: \"Billy Knott had an immense debut. He has energy, passion, drive, everything that I like in a player, and on top of that he's got Premiership quality with his left foot.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Oxford Utd 2 - 2 Wycombe|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23736909|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=24 August 2013}}</ref> He settled into the first team at [[Adams Park]], and his loan spell was twice extended.<ref>{{cite news|title=Billy Knott extends Wycombe loan stay from Sunderland|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24078566|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=13 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sunderland's Billy Knott extends Wycombe Wanderers loan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25138370|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=28 November 2013}}</ref> On 14 September, he scored his first goal for the \"Chairboys\", in a 3\u20130 win over [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Plymouth 0 - 3 Wycombe|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23999284|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=14 September 2013}}</ref> He was re-called by Sunderland on 13 January, 16 days before his loan spell was due to end.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sunderland recall Billy Knott from Wycombe Wanderers loan spell|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25714970|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=13 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 January 2014, Knott joined [[EFL League One|League One]] club Port Vale on loan for the remainder of the [[2013\u201314 Port Vale F.C. season|2013\u201314]] season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Port Vale sign Sunderland's Billy Knott|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25847254|accessdate=22 January 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=22 January 2014}}</ref> He scored his first goal at [[Vale Park]] with a left-footed strike from 25-yards on 22 March, in a 3\u20132 win over [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Port Vale 3 - 2 Tranmere Rovers|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26589252|accessdate=24 March 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=22 March 2014}}</ref> In doing so he boosted his chances of winning a contract from \"Valiants\" manager [[Micky Adams]] when his contract at Sunderland expired in the summer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Billy Knott playing for contract next season|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Port-Vale-Billy-Knott-playing-contract-season/story-20839807-detail/story.html|accessdate=24 March 2014|newspaper=[[The Sentinel (Staffordshire)|The Sentinel]]|date=22 March 2014}}</ref> On 1 April, he scored with a 20-yard strike in a 2\u20131 home win over [[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]] that was later voted as the club's Goal of the Season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Baggaley|first=Mike|title=Tom Pope named Port Vale player of the year|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Tom-Pope-named-Port-Vale-player-year/story-21056123-detail/story.html|accessdate=5 May 2014|newspaper=[[The Sentinel (Staffordshire)|The Sentinel]]|date=5 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505201838/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Tom-Pope-named-Port-Vale-player-year/story-21056123-detail/story.html|archive-date=5 May 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Bradford City===\nKnott signed a two-year contract with League One club [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in May 2014, and stated that \"[having heard] manager [[Phil Parkinson]]'s plans to take the club forward you can't really turn that down.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Billy Knott signs from Sunderland|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27639410|accessdate=30 May 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=30 May 2014}}</ref> Knott made his debut on 9 August in a 3\u20132 win against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] at [[Valley Parade]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28646631 \"Bradford City 3-2 Coventry City\"] BBC Sport. 9 August 2014. Retrieved 9 August 2014.</ref> Knott scored his first goal for the \"Bantams\" on 19 August, in a 3\u20131 win away to [[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28750066 \"Crawley Town 1-3 Bradford City\"] BBC Sport. 19 August 2014. Retrieved 19 August 2014.</ref> On 27 August, he scored in a 2\u20131 win against [[West Yorkshire derby|West Yorkshire rivals]] [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in the Second Round of the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28862805 \"Bradford City 2-1 Leeds United\"] BBC Sport. 27 August 2014. Retrieved 27 August 2014.</ref> On 24 January, he played the first 80 minutes of City's 4\u20132 [[FA Cup]] [[Chelsea F.C. 2\u20134 Bradford City A.F.C. (2015)|giant-killing]] of [[Premier League]] champions [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]], which he described as the greatest achievement of his career.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chelsea 2 - 4 Bradford|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30860394|accessdate=7 February 2015|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=24 January 2015}}</ref> After the game, he received a signed shirt from \"Blues\" captain [[John Terry]], which he passed on to his Chelsea-supporting father.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Parker|first1=Simon|title=Gone but Knott forgotten thanks to one magic moment against Leeds|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/14536024.Gone_but_Knott_forgotten_thanks_to_one_magic_moment_against_Leeds/|accessdate=24 October 2016|work=Bradford Telegraph and Argus|date=3 June 2016}}</ref> In the next round he helped Bradford beat another Premier League team, as they ran out 2\u20130 winners over his former club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bradford 2 - 0 Sunderland|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31423096|accessdate=16 February 2015|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=15 February 2015}}</ref> However, he lost his first team place to [[Josh Cullen]], and was released at the end of the [[2015\u201316 Bradford City A.F.C. season|2015\u201316]] season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Parker|first1=Simon|title=Knott confirms Bradford City exit|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/14521008.Knott_confirms_Bradford_City_exit/?ref=arc|accessdate=28 May 2016|work=Telegraph & Argus|date=27 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Gillingham===\nIn June 2016, Knott signed a two-year contract with League One club [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Billy Knott: Gillingham sign former Bradford City midfielder|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36548354|accessdate=16 June 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=16 June 2016}}</ref> Manager [[Justin Edinburgh]] said he was \"a very bright talent\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cawdell|first1=Luke|title=Former Chelsea and Sunderland youngster Billy Knott signs for Gillingham after release from Bradford City|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/sport/gills-news-edinburgh-transfers-97477/|accessdate=16 June 2016|work=Kent Online|date=16 June 2016}}</ref> He struggled for form at [[Priestfield Stadium|Priestfield]] early in [[2016\u201317 Gillingham F.C. season|the season]] as he said he was \"playing on the left in a diamond... but I would rather play top or bottom of the diamond to get on the ball\"; he then was sidelined with a hamstring injury before manager Edinburgh was sacked in favour of [[Adrian Pennock]] in January.<ref>{{cite news|last1=whiley|first1=Mark|title=Lincoln City sign midfielder Billy Knott from Gillingham|url=http://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/lincoln-city-sign-midfielder-billy-knott-from-gillingham/story-30107067-detail/story.html|accessdate=2 February 2017|work=Lincolnshire Live|date=2 February 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203081227/http://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/lincoln-city-sign-midfielder-billy-knott-from-gillingham/story-30107067-detail/story.html|archive-date=3 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Lincoln City===\nOn 2 February 2017, Knott joined [[National League (division)|National League]] side [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] on loan for the remainder of the [[2016\u201317 National League|2016\u201317]] campaign.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Gills' Knott Joins On Loan |url=http://www.redimps.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/gills-knott-joins-on-loan-3552099.aspx |publisher=Lincoln City Official Site |date=2 February 2017 |accessdate=2 February 2017}}</ref> On 1 April, he scored the only goal of the game against [[Bromley F.C.|Bromley]] at [[Sincil Bank]] to send the \"Imps\" to the top of the table; speaking after the game, manager [[Danny Cowley]] said Knott was a \"super-talented kid... [who] can be whatever he wants to be\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Whiley|first1=Mark|title='The break he needed' - Cowley hails quality of Billy Knott|url=http://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/the-break-he-needed-lincoln-city-boss-hails-quality-of-match-winner-billy-knott/story-30243242-detail/story.html|accessdate=13 May 2017|work=Lincolnshire Live|date=1 April 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402001557/http://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/the-break-he-needed-lincoln-city-boss-hails-quality-of-match-winner-billy-knott/story-30243242-detail/story.html|archive-date=2 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Lincoln achieved promotion back to the [[English Football League]] as National League champions with a 2\u20131 home win over [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] on 22 April.<ref name=\"Andrew Aloia\">{{cite news|last1=Aloia|first1=Andrew|title=Lincoln City 2-1 Macclesfield Town|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39605164|accessdate=13 May 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=22 April 2017}}</ref> He secured his release from Gillingham, and signed a one-year deal at Lincoln City in June 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Billy Knott: Lincoln City sign Gillingham midfielder|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40423028|accessdate=27 June 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=27 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking in September 2017, he stated that his growing maturity was the key to his recent good form.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marshall|first1=David|title=Billy Knott 'maturing' under managers he trusts at Lincoln City|url=http://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/billy-knott-maturing-under-managers-442093|accessdate=11 January 2018|work=Lincolnshire Live|date=8 September 2017}}</ref> However he struggled for form after being sent off later in the month and lost his place in the starting eleven.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Whiley |first1=Mark |title='Not how I wanted it to end' - Knott confirms Imps exit |url=https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/not-how-wanted-end-billy-1594185 |accessdate=4 June 2018 |work=lincolnshirelive |date=22 May 2018}}</ref> On 11 January 2018, Knott moved to [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] on loan until the end of the [[2017\u201318 Rochdale A.F.C. season|2017\u201318]] season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Billy Knott: Rochdale sign Lincoln City midfielder on loan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42655550|accessdate=11 January 2018|work=BBC Sport|date=11 January 2018}}</ref> However he started just once and made three substitute appearances for [[Keith Hill (footballer)|Keith Hill]]'s \"Dale\". Having struggled with depression for years, his tough time at [[Spotland Stadium|Spotland]] led him to drink heavily and as a result he contacted the [[Professional Footballers' Association]]; speaking in May 2018 he stated that \"I know I still have a way to go but I will get through this\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Billy Knott's battle with depression: The best way to deal with my life was to pass out through drink|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/sport/16218490.Billy_Knott_s_battle_with_depression__The_best_way_to_deal_with_my_life_was_to_pass_out_through_drink/?ref=mrb&lp=1|accessdate=10 May 2018|work=Echo|date=10 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> He was released by Lincoln at the end of the 2017\u201318 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44229342|title=Lincoln City: Long, Walton & Whitehouse offered new contracts|date=23 May 2018|accessdate=24 May 2018|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Concord Rangers===\nOn 4 June 2018, following his release from Lincoln, Knott dropped down two tiers to join [[National League South]] side [[Concord Rangers F.C.|Concord Rangers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.concordrangers.co.uk/welcome-billy-knott/|title=Welcome Billy Knott!|date=4 June 2018|accessdate=4 June 2018|publisher=Concord Rangers Official Site}}</ref> On the opening day of the [[2018\u201319 National League|2018\u201319]] campaign, he made his Concord debut during their 2\u20130 home victory over [[Gloucester City A.F.C.|Gloucester City]], featuring for 86 minutes before being replaced by D'sean Theobalds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2018/08/04/england/conference-n--s/concord-rangers-fc/gloucester-city-fc/2816908/|title=Concord Rangers vs. Gloucester City|date=4 August 2018|accessdate=9 September 2018|publisher=Soccerway}}</ref> Just over a month later, he scored his first goal for the club against former side, Woking, netting a late equaliser in the 92nd minute during the 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2018/09/08/england/conference-n--s/concord-rangers-fc/woking-fc/2816996/|title=Concord Rangers vs. Woking|date=8 September 2018|accessdate=9 September 2018|publisher=Soccerway}}</ref>\n\n===Chelmsford City===\nOn 15 March 2019, Knott signed for fellow [[Essex]]-based National League South club [[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelmsfordcityfc.com/news/city-seal-knott-signing-2406903.html|title=City seal Knott signing|date=15 March 2019|accessdate=15 March 2019|publisher=Chelmsford City F.C.}}</ref> He made six league appearances to help the \"Clarets\" to qualify for the play-offs with a fourth-place finish at the end of the [[2018\u201319 National League|2018\u201319]] season. However they lost out 3\u20132 to [[Welling United F.C.|Welling United]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Page |first1=Stephen |title=Chelmsford City suffer play off heartache again after loss to Welling |url=https://www.essexlive.news/sport/football/chelmsford-city-fc-lose-vanarama-2835929 |accessdate=20 May 2019 |work=essexlive |date=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nKnott has represented England at [[England national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]] and [[England national under-20 football team|under-20]] level. He scored for the under-17s in a 7\u20130 win over [[Estonia national under-17 football team|Estonia]] in a [[2009 UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship qualifying round|qualifier]] for the [[2009 UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship|2009 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] on 24 October 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=England 7 - 0 Estonia |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/fixturesresults/round=15211/match=302109/index.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130105040454/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/fixturesresults/round=15211/match=302109/index.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=5 January 2013 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=22 January 2014 }}</ref> [[Brian Eastick]] selected Knott and Sunderland teammate [[Blair Adams]] in the 21 man squad for the [[2011 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] in [[Colombia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Head Coach Brian Eastick names his squad for World Cup in Colombia|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/mens-u20s/News/2011/world-cup-squad-announced|work=thefa.com|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nKnott is a left-footed midfielder with a 'high-intensity, high-energy' playing style.<ref>{{cite news|title=Old boy Ainsworth tips Billy Knott to impress |url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Port-Vale-Vale-old-boy-Ainsworth-tips-Knott/story-20481849-detail/story.html|accessdate=23 January 2014|newspaper=[[The Sentinel (Staffordshire)|The Sentinel]]|date=23 January 2014}}</ref> He prefers to play as an attacking midfielder, but can also play on the left-side of midfield.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bate|first1=Adam|title=Billy Knott interview: Gillingham man on England dreams and future plans|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11720/10556831/billy-knott-interview-gillingham-man-on-england-dreams-and-future-plans|accessdate=2 February 2017|work=Sky Sports|date=1 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020.}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2010\u201311]]<ref name=\"Games played by Billy Knott in 2010/2011\">{{Soccerbase season|id=58463|season=2010|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2011\u201312]]<ref name=\"Games played by Billy Knott in 2011/2012\">{{Soccerbase season|id=58463|season=2011|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2012\u201313]]<ref name=\"2012-13\">Appearances and goals for this season are taken from:<br>{{Soccerbase season|id=58463|season=2012|accessdate=1 January 2017}}<br>{{Cite web| title = Woking vs. Farnborough 7&nbsp;\u2013 0| url = https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2012/11/24/england/fa-trophy/woking-fc/farnborough-fc/1413108/| publisher = Soccerway| accessdate = 13 April 2013}}<br>{{Cite web| title = Woking vs. Welling United 0&nbsp;\u2013 1| url = https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2012/12/15/england/fa-trophy/woking-fc/welling-united-fc/1415852/| publisher = Soccerway| accessdate = 19 May 2013}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|1||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2013\u201314]]<ref name=\"2013-14\">{{Soccerbase season|id=58463|season=2013|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!1!!0!!0!!0!!0!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!1!!0\n|-\n|[[AFC Wimbledon]] (loan)\n|[[2011\u201312 AFC Wimbledon season|2011\u201312]]<ref name=\"Games played by Billy Knott in 2011/2012\"/>\n|[[EFL League Two|League Two]]\n|20||3||0||0||0||0||0||0||20||3\n|-\n|[[Woking F.C.|Woking]] (loan)\n|[[2012\u201313 Football Conference|2012\u201313]]<ref name=\"2012-13\"/>\n|[[National League (division)|Conference Premier]]\n|20||8||0||0||