\n|[[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] (loan)\n|[[2017\u201318 Rochdale A.F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"2017/18\"/>\n|EFL League One\n|4||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||4||0\n|-\n|[[Concord Rangers F.C.|Concord Rangers]]\n|[[2018\u201319 National League|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"soccerway\">{{Soccerway|billy-knott/178261}}</ref>\n|[[National League South]]\n|11||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||11||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]]\n|[[2018\u201319 National League|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"soccerway\"/>\n|National League South\n|6||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1<ref group=lower-alpha name=pof>Appearance(s) in play-offs</ref>||0||7||0\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 National League|2019\u201320]]<ref name=\"soccerway\"/>\n|National League South\n|20||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1<ref group=lower-alpha name=FAT/>||1||21||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!26!!0!!0!!0!!0!!0!!2!!1!!28!!1\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!224!!20!!18!!3!!7!!2!!14!!5!!263!!31\n|}\n\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Honours==\n;Lincoln City\n*[[National League (division)|National League]] champion: [[2016\u201317 National League|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"Andrew Aloia\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knott, Billy}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Canvey Island]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:AFC Wimbledon players]]\n[[Category:Woking F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Wycombe Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Port Vale F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gillingham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Lincoln City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rochdale A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Concord Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chelmsford City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSunderland:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Knott"}
{"title_page": "Digital media player", "text_new": "{{redirect|Media extender|the extenders that connect to [[Windows Media Center]]s|Windows Media Center Extender}}\n{{redirect|Digital media receiver|amplifying audio/video receivers (a.k.a. digital media renderers)|AV receivers}}\n{{distinguish|Portable media player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=November 2013}}\n{{original research|date=November 2013}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Roku XDS with Remote.jpg|right|thumb|[[Roku]] is a popular brand of digital media players]]\n\nA '''digital media player''' (also sometimes known as a '''streaming device''' or '''streaming box''')<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techhive.com/article/3187462/best-media-streaming-device.html|title=Best media streaming devices|date=2019-12-16|website=TechHive|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> is a type of [[consumer electronics]] device designed for the storage, playback, or viewing of [[digital media]] content. They are typically designed to be integrated into a [[home cinema]] configuration, and attached to a [[television]] and/or [[AV receiver]].\n\nThe term is most synonymous with devices designed primarily for the consumption of content from [[streaming media]] services such as [[internet video]], including subscription-based [[Over-the-top media service|over-the-top content services]]. These devices usually have a compact form factor (either as a compact [[set-top box]], or a [[dongle]] designed to plug into an [[HDMI]] port), and contain a [[10-foot user interface]] with support for a [[remote control]] and, in some cases, [[Speech recognition|voice command]]s, as control schemes. Some services may support remote control on digital media players using their respective [[mobile app]]s, while [[Google]]'s [[Chromecast]] line is designed exclusively around this method of operation.\n\nA digital media player's operating system may provide a [[Web search engine|search engine]] for locating content available across multiple services and installed apps. Many digital media players offer internal access to [[digital distribution]] platforms, where users can download or purchase content such as films, television episodes, and [[App store|apps]]. In addition to internet sources, digital media players may support the playback of content from other sources, such as external media (including [[USB flash drive|USB drives]] or [[memory card]]s), or streamed from a [[computer]] or [[media server]]. Some digital media players may also support [[video game]]s, though their complexity (which can range from [[casual game]]s to ports of larger games) depends on operating system and hardware support, and besides those marketed as [[microconsoles]], are not usually promoted as the device's main function.\n\nDigital media players do not usually include a [[Tuner (radio)|tuner]] for receiving television service, nor disc drives for [[DVD]] or [[Blu-ray disc]]s. Some devices, such as standalone Blu-ray players, may include similar functions to digital media players (often in a reduced form), as well as recent generations of [[video game console]]s, while \"[[smart TV]]s\" integrate similar functions into the television itself. Some TV makers have, in turn, licensed operating system platforms from digital media players as [[middleware]] for their smart TVs\u2014such as [[Android TV]], [[Amazon Fire TV]], and [[Roku]]\u2014which typically provide a similar user experience to their standalone counterparts, but with TV-specific features and settings reflected in their user interface.\n\n==Overview==\nIn the 2010s, with the popularity of [[portable media player]]s and [[digital camera]]s, as well as fast Internet download speeds and relatively cheap mass storage, many people came into possession of large collections of digital media files that cannot be played on a conventional analog [[HiFi]] without connecting a computer to an amplifier or television. The means to play these files on a network-connected ug digital media player that is permanently connected to a television is seen as a convenience. The rapid growth in the availability of online content has made it easier for consumers to use these devices and obtain content.  [[YouTube]], for instance, is a common plug-in available on most networked devices.  [[Netflix]] has also struck deals with many consumer-electronics makers to make their interface available in the device's menus, for their streaming subscribers.  This symbiotic relationship between Netflix and consumer electronics makers has helped propel Netflix to become the largest subscription video service in the U.S.,<ref>{{cite news | last = Narcisse | first = Evan | title = Netflix Becoming Largest Subscription Entertainment Company | work = | pages = | publisher = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date = 25 April 2011 | url = http://techland.time.com/2011/04/25/netflix-becoming-largest-subscription-entertainment-company/ | accessdate = 2 May 2011}}</ref> using up to 20% of U.S. bandwidth at peak times.<ref>{{cite news|last=Liedtke |first=Michael |title=Netflix expects video streaming to drown out DVDs |work= |pages= |agency=Associated Press |date=22 November 2010 |url=http://www.valleynewslive.com/Global/story.asp?S=13551980&clienttype=printable |accessdate=7 February 2011 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nMedia players are often designed for compactness and affordability, and tend to have small or non-existent hardware displays other than simple [[LED]] lights to indicate whether the device is powered on. Interface navigation on the television is usually done with an [[infrared]] [[remote control]], while more-advanced digital media players come with high-performance [[remote control]]s which allow control of the interface using integrated touch sensors. Some remotes also include [[accelerometer]]s for [[air mouse]] features which allow basic motion gaming.  Most digital media player devices are unable to play physical audio or video media directly, and instead require a user to convert these media into playable digital files using a separate computer and software. They are also usually incapable of recording audio or video. In the 2010s, it is also common to find digital media player functionality integrated into other consumer-electronics appliances, such as [[DVD player]]s, [[set-top box]]es, [[smart TV]]s, or even [[video game console]]s.\n\n==Terminology==\nDigital media players are also commonly referred to as a \"digital media extender\", \"digital media streamer\", \"digital media hub\", \"digital media adapter\", or \"digital media receiver\" (which should not be confused with ''[[AV Receiver]]'' that are also called ''Digital Media Renderer'').<ref>https://us.en.kb.sony.com/app/answers/detail/a_id/35234 {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20131107174008/https://us.en.kb.sony.com/app/answers/detail/a_id/35234 |date=7 November 2013 }} What are the differences in DLNA device classes?</ref><ref>http://hometheater.about.com/od/interactivetelevision/a/Dlna-Certifications-The-Role-Of-Each-Network-Media-Component-In-Media-Sharing.htm DLNA Certifications - The Role of Each Network Media Component in Media Sharing</ref>\n\nDigital media player manufacturers use a variety of names to describe their devices. Some more commonly used alternative names include:\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* Connected DVD\n* Connected media player\n* Digital audio receiver\n* Digital media adapter\n* Digital media connect\n* Digital media extender\n* Digital media hub\n* Digital media player\n* Digital media streamer\n* Digital media receiver\n* Digital media renderer\n* Digital video receiver\n* Digital video streamer\n* HD Media Player\n* HDD media player\n* Media Extender\n* Media Regulator\n* Net connected media player\n* Network connected media player\n* Network media player\n* Networked Digital Video Disc\n* Networked entertainment gateway\n* Smart Television media player\n* Smart Television player\n* Streaming media box\n* Streaming media player\n* Streaming video player\n* Wireless Media Adapter\n* OTT player\n* Over-the-Top player\n* YouTube Player Support\n{{div col end}}\n\n==History==\nBy November 2000, an audio-only digital media player was demonstrated by a company called SimpleDevices, which was awarded two patents covering this invention in 2006.<ref>{{cite patent|US|7130616}}</ref><ref>{{cite patent|US|6993289}}</ref> Developed under the SimpleFi name by [[Motorola]] in late 2001, the design was based on a Cirrus Arm-7 processor and the wireless [[HomeRF]] networking standard which pre-dated 802.11b in the residential markets.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Motorola Simplefi review |work= CNet |date= 16 August 2002 |url= http://reviews.cnet.com/digital-audio-receivers-dars/motorola-simplefi/4505-6470_7-9050945.html |accessdate= 14 September 2013 }}</ref> Other early market entrants in 2001 included the [[AudioTron|Turtle Beach AudioTron]], [[Rio Receiver]] and [[Squeezebox (network music player)#SliMP3 .282001.29|SliMP3]] digital media players. An early version of a video-capable digital media player was presented by F.C. Jeng et al. in the International Conf. on Consumer Electronics in 2002.<ref>F.C. Jeng, M. Jeanson, S-Y Zhu, and K. Konstantinides, [https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1013945 \"Design of a home media center with network and streaming capabilities\"], IEEE Intern. Conf. on Consumer Electronics, 2002, pp. 102-103.</ref> It included a network interface card, a media processor for audio and video decoding, an analog video encoder (for video playback to a TV), an audio digital to analog converter for audio playback, and an IR (infrared receiver) for remote-control-interface.\n\nA concept of a digital media player was also introduced by Intel in 2002 at the [[Intel Developer Forum]] as part of their \u201cExtended Wireless PC Initiative.\"  Intel's digital media player was based on an Xscale PXA210 processor and supported 802.11b wireless networking. Intel was among the first to use the Linux embedded operating system and [[UPnP]] technology for its digital media player. Networked audio and DVD players were among the first consumer devices to integrate digital media player functionality. Examples include the Philips [[Streamium]]-range of products that allowed for remote streaming of audio, the GoVideo D2730 Networked DVD player which integrated DVD playback with the capability to stream Rhapsody audio from a PC, and the Buffalo LinkTheater which combined a DVD player with a digital media player.  More recently, the Xbox 360 gaming console from Microsoft was among the first gaming devices that integrated a digital media player. With the Xbox 360, Microsoft also introduced the concept of a [[Windows Media Center Extender]], which allows users to access the Media center capabilities of a PC remotely, through a home network.  More recently, Linksys, D-Link, and HP introduced the latest generation of digital media players that support 720p and 1080p high resolution video playback and may integrate both Windows Extender and traditional digital media player functionality.\n\n==Typical features==\nA digital media player can connect to the home network using either a wireless ([[IEEE 802.11a-1999|IEEE 802.11a]], b, g, and n) or wired [[Ethernet]] connection. Digital media players includes a user interface that allows users to navigate through their digital media library, search for, and play back media files. Some digital media players only handle music; some handle music and pictures; some handle music, pictures, and video; while others go further to allow internet browsing or controlling Live TV from a PC with a TV tuner.\n\nSome other capabilities which are accomplished by digital media players include:\n* Play, catalog, and store local [[hard disk]], [[USB flash drive|flash drive]], or [[memory card]] music [[CD]]s and view CD album art, view digital photos, and watch [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] or other videos.\n* Stream movies, music, photos (media) over the wired or wireless network<ref>{{cite web|title=Airplay|url=https://www.apple.com/airplay/|publisher=apple.com}}</ref>\n* View digital pictures (one by one or as picture [[slideshow]]s)\n* Stream online video to a TV from services such as [[Netflix]] and [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Google TV|url=https://www.google.com/tv/apps.html|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n*Play video games such as [[Angry Birds]] and others.<ref>{{cite web|last=White|first=Charlie|title=Now You Can Play Angry Birds On a Roku 2 [PICS]|url=http://mashable.com/2011/08/06/roku-2-xs-review/|publisher=mashable.com|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n*Browse the Internet, check email and access [[social networking]] sites like [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]], [[LinkedIn]] on TV through downloadable applications.\n*[[Videotelephony|Video conference]] by connecting a [[webcam]] and microphone.<ref name=\"amkette1\"/>\n\nIn the 2010s, there are stand-alone digital media players on the market from AC Ryan, Asus, Apple (e.g., [[Apple TV]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Barlow|first=Graham|title=Apple TV review|url=http://www.techradar.com/reviews/audio-visual/av-accessories/apple-tv-900409/review|publisher=techradar.com|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>), NetGear (e.g., NTV and NeoTV models), Dune, iOmega, [[Logitech]], Pivos Group, Micca, Sybas (Popcorn Hour), [[Amkette EvoTV]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Almeida|first=Aaron|title=Amkette EvoTV Review|url=http://tech2.in.com/reviews/hd-media-players/amkette-evotv-review/323422|publisher=tech2.in.com|accessdate=17 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712161933/http://tech2.in.com/reviews/hd-media-players/amkette-evotv-review/323422|archivedate=12 July 2012}}</ref> D-Link,  EZfetch, [[Fire TV]], [[Android TV]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Greenwald|first=Will|title=Sony Internet Player With Google TV (NSZ-GS7)|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2413422,00.asp|publisher=pcmag.com|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref> Pinnacle, [[Xtreamer]], and [[Roku]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Biddle|first=Sam|title=Roku 3 Review: The New Best Streaming Box|url=https://gizmodo.com/5991159/roku-3-review-the-new-best-streaming-box|publisher=gizmodo.com|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref> just to name a few. The models change frequently, so it is advisable to visit their web sites for current model names.\n\n===Processors===\nThese devices come with low power consumption processors or [[System on a chip|SoC (System on Chip)]] and are most commonly either based on [[MIPS architecture|MIPS]] or [[ARM architecture]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Cortex-A9 Processor|url=http://www.arm.com/products/processors/cortex-a/cortex-a9.php|publisher=arm.com}}</ref> processors combined with integrated [[Digital signal processing|DSP]] [[Graphics processing unit|GPU]] in a [[System on a chip|SoC]] (or [[MPSoC]]) package. They also include [[RAM]]-memory and some type of built-in [[Flash memory|type of non-volatile computer memory (Flash memory)]].<ref name=\"amkette1\">{{cite web|title=Amkette|url=http://amkette.com/product.jsp?id=185|publisher=Amkette|accessdate=17 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524194023/http://amkette.com/product.jsp?id=185|archive-date=24 May 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Internal hard-drive capabilities===\n''HD media player'' or ''HDD media player'' (''HDMP'') is a consumer product that combines digital media player with a [[hard drive]] (HD) [[disk enclosure|enclosure]] with all the hardware and software for playing [[Content (media and publishing)|audio]], [[video]] and photos to a television. All these can play computer-based media files to a television without the need for a separate computer or network connection, and some can even be used as a conventional external hard-drive. These types of digital media players are sometimes sold as empty shells to allow the user to fit their own choice of hard drive (some can manage unlimited hard disk capacity and other only a certain capacity, i.e. 1TB, 2TB, 3TB, or 4TB), and the same model is sometimes sold with or without an internal hard drive already fitted.\n\n=== Formats, resolutions and file systems ===\nDigital media players can usually play [[H.264/MPEG-4 AVC|H.264]] (SD and [[high resolution|HD]]), [[MPEG-4 Part 2]] (SD and HD), [[MPEG-1]], [[MPEG-2]] [[.mpg]], [[MPEG-2]] .[[MPEG transport stream|TS]], [[VOB]] and [[ISO image]]s video, with [[Pulse-code modulation|PCM]], [[MP3]] and [[Dolby AC-3|AC3]] audio tracks. They can also display images (such as [[JPEG]] and [[Portable Network Graphics|PNG]]) and play music files (such as [[FLAC]], [[MP3]] and [[Ogg]]).\n\n===Operating system===\n{{main|List of smart TV platforms and middleware software}}\nWhile most media players have traditionally been running [[Proprietary software|proprietary]] or [[Open-source model|open source]] [[software framework]]s versions based [[Linux]] as their operating systems, many newer network connected media players are based on the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] platform which gives them an advantage in terms of applications and games from the [[Google Play]] store. Even without Android some digital media players still have the ability to run applications (sometimes available via an 'app store' [[digital distribution]] [[platform (computing)|platform]]), interactive on-demand media, personalized communications, and social networking features<ref>{{cite web|author= Devindra Hardawar |url=https://venturebeat.com/2010/12/08/why-your-tv-is-the-new-app-battleground/ |title=Why your TV is the new app battleground |publisher=Venturebeat.com |date=8 December 2010 |accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10132877 BBC News&nbsp;\u2013 Google launches smart TV service]. bbc.co.uk (20 May 2010). Retrieved on 11 November 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Stan Schroeder 230 |url=http://mashable.com/2010/05/17/google-intel-sony-smart-tv/ |title=Google, Intel and Sony to Introduce Smart TV |publisher=Mashable.com |date=17 May 2010 |accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialtimes.com/2010/05/opinion-will-googles-smart-tv-finally-bring-apps-and-web-browsing-to-the-living-room/ |title=Opinion: Will Google's Smart TV Finally Bring Apps and Web Browsing To The Living Room? |publisher=Socialtimes.com |date=17 May 2010 |accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10132877 |title=Google launches smart TV service |publisher=BBC |date=20 May 2010 |accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Connections ==\n[[File:Dighub3.jpg|thumb|300px|An example of a Digital media player in a network]]\nThere are two ways to connect an extender to its central [[Home theater PC|media center]] or [[HTPC]] server - wired, or wireless. A wireless connection can be established between the media extender and its central media center. On the downside, interference may cause a \"less than optimal\" connection and cause network congestion, resulting in stuttering sound, missing frames from video, and other anomalies. It is recommended{{By whom|date=September 2013}} that an [[802.11a]] or better be used, and over as short of a distance as possible.\n[[File:Digital media receiver - network music player.jpg|thumb|A wireless media extender from [[Arctic (company)|Arctic]] for music streaming and multi-room entertainment<ref>[http://www.arctic.ac/en/p/living/multi-room-system/463/audio-relay.html?c=2327 \"Audio Relay\"] Retrieved 11 October 2012</ref>]]\n\n===Streaming and communication protocols===\nWhile early digital media players used proprietary communication protocols to interface with media servers, today most digital media players either use standard-based protocols such [[Server Message Block|SMB/CIFS/SAMBA]] or [[Network File System|NFS]], or rely on some version of [[UPnP]] (Universal Plug and Play) and [[DLNA]] (Digital Living Network Alliance) standards. DLNA-compliant digital media players and Media Servers is meant to guarantee a minimum set of functionality and proper interoperability among digital media players and servers regardless of the manufacturer, but unfortunately not every manufacturer follows the standards perfectly which can lead to incompatibility.\n\n===Media server===\nSome digital media players will only connect to specific media server software installed on a PC to stream music, pictures and recorded or live TV originating from the computer. Apple iTunes can, for example, be used this way with the Apple TV hardware that connects to a TV. Apple has developed a tightly integrated device and content management ecosystem with their [[iTunes Store]], personal computers, [[iOS (Apple)|iOS]] [[List of iOS devices|devices]], and the [[AppleTV]] [[digital media receiver]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2010/10/01/how-apple-took-the-high-ground-in-the-battle-for-the-global-digital-living-room/ | title=How Apple took the high ground in the battle for the global digital living room | first=Philip | last=Elmer-DeWitt | date=1 October 2010 | publisher=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] | accessdate=13 February 2011}}</ref>  The most recent version of the AppleTV, at $99, has lost the hard-drive that was included in its predecessor and fully depends on either streaming internet content, or another computer on the home network for media.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bostonherald.com/business/technology/reviews/view/20110124apples_web_tv_packs_big_bang_for_the_buck/srvc=home&position=also | title=Apple's Web TV packs big bang for the buck | first=Brendan| last=Lynch | date=24 January 2011 | publisher=[[Boston Herald]] | accessdate=8 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Connection ports===\n[[File:Apple TV. 1st generation-2290.jpg|thumb|Back of 1st generation Apple TV]]\n[[File:Apple TV 2nd Generation back.jpg|thumb|Back of 2nd &amp; 3rd generation Apple TV]]\nTelevision connection is usually done via; composite, [[SCART]], Component, [[HDMI]] video, with Optical Audio (TOSLINK/SPDIF), and connect to the local network and [[broadband]] internet using either a wired [[Ethernet]] or a wireless [[Wi-Fi]] connection, and some also have built-in [[Bluetooth]] support for remotes and game-pads or joysticks. Some players come with [[USB]] ([[USB 2.0]] or [[USB 3.0]]) ports which allow local media content playback.\n\n== Use ==\n=== Market impact on traditional television services ===\nThe convergence of content, technology, and broadband access allows consumers to stream television shows and movies to their high-definition television in competition with [[pay television]] providers. The research company SNL Kagan expects 12 million households, roughly 10%, to go without cable, satellite or telco video service by 2015 using [[Over-the-top content|Over The Top]] services.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://blogs.forbes.com/dorothypomerantz/2011/07/20/12-million-households-expected-to-cut-the-cord-by-2015 | title=12 Million Households Expected to Cut the Cord By 2015 | date=20 July 2011 | work=[[Forbes]] | accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> This represents a new trend in the broadcast television industry, as the list of options for watching movies and TV over the Internet grows at a rapid pace. Research also shows that even as traditional television service providers are trimming their customer base, they are adding [[Broadband]] Internet customers. Nearly 76.6 million U.S. households get broadband from leading cable and telephone companies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leichtmanresearch.com/press/051711release.html |title=Nearly 1.3 Million Add Broadband in the First Quarter of 2011 |date=17 May 2011 |publisher=Leichtman Research Group |accessdate=17 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713200733/http://www.leichtmanresearch.com/press/051711release.html |archivedate=13 July 2011 }}</ref> although only a portion have sufficient speeds to support quality video steaming.<ref name=Forrester>{{cite web | url=http://www.forrester.com/rb/Research/online_video_on_tv_leads_to_cord-cutting/q/id/57160/t/2/ | title=Online Video On TV Leads To Cord-Cutting By 2012 | first=James L. | last=McQuivey, Ph.D. | date=14 March 2011 | publisher=[[Forrester Research]] | accessdate=22 July 2011}}</ref> Convergence devices for home entertainment will likely play a much larger role in the future of broadcast television, effectively shifting traditional revenue streams while providing consumers with more options.<ref name=Forrester/>\n\nAccording to a report from the researcher NPD In-Stat, only about 12 million U.S. households have their either Web-capable TVs or digital media players connected to the Internet, although In-Stat estimates about 25 million U.S. TV households own a set with the built-in network capability. Also, In-Stat predicts that 100 million homes in North America and western Europe will own digital media players and television sets that blend traditional programs with Internet content by 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2012/03/100-million-tvs-will-be-internet-connected-by-2016.html|title=100 million TVs will be Internet-connected by 2016|work=latimes.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Use for illegal streaming ===\nSince at least 2015,<ref name=\"engadget-sellerskodi\">{{cite web|title=Kodi takes the fight to sellers of pirate TV boxes|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/02/14/kodi-takes-the-fight-to-sellers-of-pirate-tv-boxes/|website=Engadget|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"tf-kodiban\">{{cite web|title=Amazon Bans Kodi/XBMC App Over Piracy Concerns|url=https://torrentfreak.com/amazon-bans-kodi-app-over-piracy-concerns-150616/|website=TorrentFreak|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"techhive-amazon\">{{cite web|title=Amazon pulls popular video app Kodi from its store, blames piracy|url=http://www.techhive.com/article/2937028/amazon-pulls-popular-video-app-kodi-from-its-store-blames-piracy.html|website=TechHive|publisher=IDG|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"tf-firestickuk\">{{cite web|title=Did Pirates Clean Out Amazon Fire TV Stock in the UK?|url=https://torrentfreak.com/did-pirates-clean-out-amazon-fire-tv-stock-in-the-uk-151229/|website=TorrentFreak|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> dealers have marketed digital media players, often running the Android operating system and branded as being \"'''fully-loaded'''\", that are promoted as offering free streaming access to copyrighted media content, including films and television programs, as well as [[Pirate decryption|live feeds of television channels]]. These players are commonly bundled with the open source media player software [[Kodi (software)|Kodi]], which is in turn pre-loaded with [[Plug-in (computing)|plug-ins]] enabling access to services streaming this content without the permission of their respective copyright holders. These \"fully-loaded\" set-top boxes are often sold through online marketplaces such as [[Amazon.com]] and [[eBay]], as well as local retailers.<ref name=\"cbc-freetv\"/><ref name=\"ars-fullyloadedkodi\" /> The spread of these players has been attributed to their ease of use (with user experiences similar to legal subscription services such as [[Netflix]]) and low cost, as well as the content that is offered from the services pre-installed on the boxes.<ref name=\"ars-fullyloadedkodi\">{{cite web|title=Kodi: Open source TV app inspires full-blown copyright panic in the UK|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/05/kodi-fully-loaded-boxes-are-they-legal/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"cbc-pirateboxes\">{{cite web|title='Free TV' Android boxes finding their way into many Canadian households, study says|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/piracy-android-box-free-tv-1.4098249|website=CBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"cbc-freetv\">{{cite web|title=Free TV for life? It's here, and it may even be legal|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/android-box-streaming-1.3455524|website=CBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"Fully-loaded\" set-top boxes have been subject to legal controversies, especially noting that their user experiences made them accessible to end-users who may not always realize that they are actually streaming pirated content.<ref name=\"ars-fullyloadedkodi\" /><ref name=\"cbc-pirateboxes\" /> In the United Kingdom, the [[Federation Against Copyright Theft]] (FACT) has taken court actions on behalf of rightsholders against those who market digital media players pre-loaded with access to copyrighted content. In January 2017, an individual seller plead not guilty to charges of marketing and distributing devices that [[Anti-circumvention|circumvent]] [[technological protection measures]].<ref name=\"bbc-notguilty\">{{cite web|title=Not guilty plea in landmark Kodi box trial|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-38769045|website=BBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc-fullyloadedtest\">{{cite web|title=Sale of Kodi 'fully-loaded' streaming boxes faces legal test|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-37474595|website=BBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"arsuk-fivearrests\">{{cite web|title=Five suspects arrested for sale of \"fully loaded\" Kodi streaming boxes|url=https://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2017/02/five-suspects-arrested-for-sale-of-fully-loaded-kodi-streaming-boxes/|website=Ars Technica UK|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, the [[High Court of Justice]] ruled that [[BT Group]], [[Sky plc]], [[TalkTalk TV|TalkTalk]], and [[Virgin Media]] must block servers that had been used on such set-top boxes to illegally stream [[Premier League]] football games.<ref name=\"ars-kodicrackdown\">{{cite web|title=Kodi crackdown: Premier League wins High Court order to block illegal streams|url=https://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2017/03/kodi-crackdown-premier-league-high-court-order-block-illegal-streams/|website=Ars Technica UK|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> Later in the month, [[Amazon UK]] banned the sale of \"certain media players\" that had been pre-loaded with software to illegally stream copyrighted content.<ref name=\"arsuk-amazonban\">{{cite web|title=Amazon bans \"certain\" media streamers, but are Kodi-loaded boxes barred?|url=https://arstechnica.co.uk/gadgets/2017/04/amazon-uk-kodi-media-streamer-ban/|website=Ars Technica UK|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> On 26 April 2017, the [[European Court of Justice]] ruled that the distribution of set-top boxes with access to unauthorized streams of copyrighted works violated the exclusive rights to communicate them to the public.<ref name=\"ars-fullyloadedkodi\"/> In September 2017, a British seller of such boxes pled guilty to violations of the [[Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988|Copyright, Designs and Patents Act]] for selling devices that can circumvent effective [[technical protection measures]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/landmark-kodi-trial-dissolved-due-to-guilty-plea/|title=Landmark loaded Kodi box trial dissolves with guilty plea|last=Osborne|first=Charlie|work=ZDNet|access-date=26 September 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn Canada, it was initially believed that these set-top boxes fell within a legal grey area, as the transient nature of streaming content did not necessarily mean that the content was being downloaded in violation of [[Canadian copyright law]].<ref name=\"cbc-freetv\"/> However, on 1 June 2016, a consortium of Canadian media companies ([[BCE Inc.]], [[Rogers Communications]], and [[Videotron]]) obtained a temporary federal injunction against five retailers of Android-based set-top boxes, alleging that their continued sale were causing \"irreparable harm\" to their television businesses, and that the devices' primary purpose were to facilitate copyright infringement. The court rejected an argument by one of the defendants, who stated that they were only marketing a hardware device with publicly available software, ruling that the defendants were \"deliberately encourag[ing] consumers and potential clients to circumvent authorized ways of accessing content.\"<ref name=\"cbc-freetvcourt\"/><ref name=\"cbc-freetvcourt\">{{cite web|title=Cable companies launch court battle against 'free TV' Android box vendors|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/free-tv-loaded-android-box-cable-1.3633331|website=CBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> 11 additional defendants were subsequently added to the suit. The lawyer of one of the defendants argued that retailers should not be responsible for the actions of their users, as any type of computing device could theoretically be used for legal or illegal purposes.<ref name=\"cbc-moredefendants\">{{cite web|title=Cable companies take more Android box dealers to court to stamp out 'free TV'|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/free-tv-android-box-cable-companies-challenge-1.3660656|website=CBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> In April 2017, the [[Federal Court of Appeal]] blocked an appeal requesting that the injunction be lifted pending the outcome of the case.<ref name=\"cbc-boxappeal\">{{cite web|title='Free TV' Android box dealers lose court appeal to lift sales ban|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/android-box-free-tv-bell-rogers-1.4033741|website=CBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the software is free to use, the developers of Kodi have not endorsed any add-on or Kodi-powered device intended for facilitating copyright infringement.  Nathan Betzen, president of the XBMC Foundation (the non-profit organization which oversees the development of the Kodi software), argued that the reputation of Kodi had been harmed by third-party retailers who \"make a quick buck modifying Kodi, installing broken piracy add-ons, advertising that Kodi lets you watch free movies and TV, and then vanishing when the user buys the box and finds out that the add-on they were sold on was a crummy, constantly breaking mess.\" Betzen stated that the XBMC Foundation was willing to enforce its [[trademark]]s against those who use them to promote Kodi-based products which facilitate copyright infringement.<ref name=\"tf-legalaction\">{{cite web|title=Kodi Announces Legal Action to Smash Piracy Links|url=https://torrentfreak.com/kodi-announces-legal-action-to-smash-piracy-links-160215/|website=TorrentFreak|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"engadget-sellerskodi\"/>\n\nFollowing a lawsuit by [[Dish Network]] against TVAddons, a website that offered streaming add-ons that were often used with Kodi and on such devices, in June 2017, the group shut down its add-ons and website. A technology analyst speculated that the service could eventually re-appear under a different name in the future, as have [[torrent tracker]]s.<ref name=\"cbc-dishlawsuit\">{{cite web|title=Streaming apps for 'free TV' Android box disappear following U.S. lawsuit threat|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/streaming-box-lawsuit-tvaddons-1.4165325?|website=CBC News|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> In June, the service's operator was also sued by the Bell/Rogers/Videotron consortium for inducing copyright infringement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://torrentfreak.com/tvaddons-returns-ugly-war-canadian-telcos-kodi-addons-170801/|title=TVAddons Returns, But in Ugly War With Canadian Telcos Over Kodi Addons - TorrentFreak|date=1 August 2017|work=TorrentFreak|access-date=2 August 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, [[Televisa]] was granted a court order banning the sale of all [[Roku]] products in Mexico, as it was alleged that third-parties had been operating subscription television services for the devices that contain unlicensed content. The content is streamed through unofficial apps that are added to the devices through hacking. Roku objected to the allegations, stating that these services were not certified by the company or part of its official Channels platform, whose terms of service require that they have rights to stream the content that they offer. Roku also stated that it actively cooperates with reports of channels that infringe copyrights.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/roku-sales-banned-mexico-piracy-1202484188/|title=Roku Device Sales Banned in Mexico Over Piracy|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=30 June 2017|work=Variety|access-date=3 July 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> The ruling was overturned in October 2018 after Roku took additional steps to remove channels with unauthorized content from the platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2018/10/17/17989598/roku-devices-mexico-sales-back-piracy-concerns-court-ruling-streaming|title=Roku devices are coming back to Mexico after court ruling|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=2018-10-17|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] sent letters to the CEOs of [[Amazon.com]] and [[eBay]], asking for their help in removing such devices from their marketplaces. The letter cited malware risks, fraudulent use of FCC certification marks, and how their distribution through major online marketplaces may incorrectly suggest that they are legal and legitimate products.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/05/29/fcc-asks-amazon-and-ebay-to-stop-selling-fake-pay-tv-boxes/|title=FCC asks Amazon and eBay to stop selling fake pay TV boxes |website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-30}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Television}}\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Comparison of digital media players]]\n*[[Cord-cutting]]\n*[[Digital Living Network Alliance]]\n*[[Digital video recorder]]\n*[[List of net-connected media players]]\n*[[List of smart TV platforms and middleware software]]\n*[[Second screen]]\n*[[Streaming media]]\n*[[System on a chip]]\n*[[Tivoization]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100315162703/http://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/reviews/4243711.html?page=7 HP MediaSmart Connect Wins Popular Mechanics Editor's Choice Award at CES 2008]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070820040205/http://reviews.cnet.com/4323-6531_7-6509113.html CNET Editors' Best Network Music Players]\n*[https://www.pcmag.com/category2/0,1874,924250,00.asp PC Magazine Media Hub & Receiver Finder]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130528013354/http://www.audiofi.co.uk/reviews/index.php AudioFi Reviews of wireless players]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080430135734/http://www.pcworld.com/article/id,108818-page,1-c,plugandplay/article.html PC World's Future Gear: PC on the HiFi, and the TV]\n\n{{Home theater PC (application software)}}\n{{Media player (application software)}}\n\n[[Category:Digital media players| ]]\n[[Category:Digital media receivers| ]]\n[[Category:Consumer electronics]]\n[[Category:Media players]]\n[[Category:Networking hardware]]\n[[Category:Television technology]]\n[[Category:Multimedia]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) devices]]\n[[Category:Digital audio]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Media extender|the extenders that connect to [[Windows Media Center]]s|Windows Media Center Extender}}\n{{redirect|Digital media receiver|amplifying audio/video receivers (a.k.a. digital media renderers)|AV receivers}}\n{{distinguish|Portable media player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=November 2013}}\n{{original research|date=November 2013}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Roku XDS with Remote.jpg|right|thumb|[[Roku]] is a popular brand of digital media players]]\n\nA '''digital media player''' (also sometimes known as a '''streaming device''' or '''streaming box''')<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techhive.com/article/3187462/best-media-streaming-device.html|title=Best media streaming devices|date=2019-12-16|website=TechHive|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> is a type of [[consumer electronics]] device designed for the storage, playback, or viewing of [[digital media]] content. They are typically designed to be integrated into a [[home cinema]] configuration, and attached to a [[television]] and/or [[AV receiver]].\n\nThe term is most synonymous with devices designed primarily for the consumption of content from [[streaming media]] services such as [[internet video]], including subscription-based [[Over-the-top media service|over-the-top content services]]. These devices usually have a compact form factor (either as a compact [[set-top box]], or a [[dongle]] designed to plug into an [[HDMI]] port), and contain a [[10-foot user interface]] with support for a [[remote control]] and, in some cases, [[Speech recognition|voice command]]s, as control schemes. Some services may support remote control on digital media players using their respective [[mobile app]]s, while [[Google]]'s [[Chromecast]] line is designed exclusively around this method of operation.\n\nA digital media player's operating system may provide a [[Web search engine|search engine]] for locating content available across multiple services and installed apps. Many digital media players offer internal access to [[digital distribution]] platforms, where users can download or purchase content such as films, television episodes, and [[App store|apps]]. In addition to internet sources, digital media players may support the playback of content from other sources, such as external media (including [[USB flash drive|USB drives]] or [[memory card]]s), or streamed from a [[computer]] or [[media server]]. Some digital media players may also support [[video game]]s, though their complexity (which can range from [[casual game]]s to ports of larger games) depends on operating system and hardware support, and besides those marketed as [[microconsoles]], are not usually promoted as the device's main function.\n\nDigital media players do not usually include a [[Tuner (radio)|tuner]] for receiving television service, nor disc drives for [[DVD]] or [[Blu-ray disc]]s. Some devices, such as standalone Blu-ray players, may include similar functions to digital media players (often in a reduced form), as well as recent generations of [[video game console]]s, while \"[[smart TV]]s\" integrate similar functions into the television itself. Some TV makers have, in turn, licensed operating system platforms from digital media players as [[middleware]] for their smart TVs\u2014such as [[Android TV]], [[Amazon Fire TV]], and [[Roku]]\u2014which typically provide a similar user experience to their standalone counterparts, but with TV-specific features and settings reflected in their user interface.\n\n==Overview==\nIn the 2010s, with the popularity of [[portable media player]]s and [[digital camera]]s, as well as fast Internet download speeds and relatively cheap mass storage, many people came into possession of large collections of digital media files that cannot be played on a conventional analog [[HiFi]] without connecting a computer to an amplifier or television. The means to play these files on a network-connected digital media player that is permanently connected to a television is seen as a convenience. The rapid growth in the availability of online content has made it easier for consumers to use these devices and obtain content.  [[YouTube]], for instance, is a common plug-in available on most networked devices.  [[Netflix]] has also struck deals with many consumer-electronics makers to make their interface available in the device's menus, for their streaming subscribers.  This symbiotic relationship between Netflix and consumer electronics makers has helped propel Netflix to become the largest subscription video service in the U.S.,<ref>{{cite news | last = Narcisse | first = Evan | title = Netflix Becoming Largest Subscription Entertainment Company | work = | pages = | publisher = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date = 25 April 2011 | url = http://techland.time.com/2011/04/25/netflix-becoming-largest-subscription-entertainment-company/ | accessdate = 2 May 2011}}</ref> using up to 20% of U.S. bandwidth at peak times.<ref>{{cite news|last=Liedtke |first=Michael |title=Netflix expects video streaming to drown out DVDs |work= |pages= |agency=Associated Press |date=22 November 2010 |url=http://www.valleynewslive.com/Global/story.asp?S=13551980&clienttype=printable |accessdate=7 February 2011 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nMedia players are often designed for compactness and affordability, and tend to have small or non-existent hardware displays other than simple [[LED]] lights to indicate whether the device is powered on. Interface navigation on the television is usually done with an [[infrared]] [[remote control]], while more-advanced digital media players come with high-performance [[remote control]]s which allow control of the interface using integrated touch sensors. Some remotes also include [[accelerometer]]s for [[air mouse]] features which allow basic motion gaming.  Most digital media player devices are unable to play physical audio or video media directly, and instead require a user to convert these media into playable digital files using a separate computer and software. They are also usually incapable of recording audio or video. In the 2010s, it is also common to find digital media player functionality integrated into other consumer-electronics appliances, such as [[DVD player]]s, [[set-top box]]es, [[smart TV]]s, or even [[video game console]]s.\n\n==Terminology==\nDigital media players are also commonly referred to as a \"digital media extender\", \"digital media streamer\", \"digital media hub\", \"digital media adapter\", or \"digital media receiver\" (which should not be confused with ''[[AV Receiver]]'' that are also called ''Digital Media Renderer'').<ref>https://us.en.kb.sony.com/app/answers/detail/a_id/35234 {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20131107174008/https://us.en.kb.sony.com/app/answers/detail/a_id/35234 |date=7 November 2013 }} What are the differences in DLNA device classes?</ref><ref>http://hometheater.about.com/od/interactivetelevision/a/Dlna-Certifications-The-Role-Of-Each-Network-Media-Component-In-Media-Sharing.htm DLNA Certifications - The Role of Each Network Media Component in Media Sharing</ref>\n\nDigital media player manufacturers use a variety of names to describe their devices. Some more commonly used alternative names include:\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* Connected DVD\n* Connected media player\n* Digital audio receiver\n* Digital media adapter\n* Digital media connect\n* Digital media extender\n* Digital media hub\n* Digital media player\n* Digital media streamer\n* Digital media receiver\n* Digital media renderer\n* Digital video receiver\n* Digital video streamer\n* HD Media Player\n* HDD media player\n* Media Extender\n* Media Regulator\n* Net connected media player\n* Network connected media player\n* Network media player\n* Networked Digital Video Disc\n* Networked entertainment gateway\n* Smart Television media player\n* Smart Television player\n* Streaming media box\n* Streaming media player\n* Streaming video player\n* Wireless Media Adapter\n* OTT player\n* Over-the-Top player\n* YouTube Player Support\n{{div col end}}\n\n==History==\nBy November 2000, an audio-only digital media player was demonstrated by a company called SimpleDevices, which was awarded two patents covering this invention in 2006.<ref>{{cite patent|US|7130616}}</ref><ref>{{cite patent|US|6993289}}</ref> Developed under the SimpleFi name by [[Motorola]] in late 2001, the design was based on a Cirrus Arm-7 processor and the wireless [[HomeRF]] networking standard which pre-dated 802.11b in the residential markets.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Motorola Simplefi review |work= CNet |date= 16 August 2002 |url= http://reviews.cnet.com/digital-audio-receivers-dars/motorola-simplefi/4505-6470_7-9050945.html |accessdate= 14 September 2013 }}</ref> Other early market entrants in 2001 included the [[AudioTron|Turtle Beach AudioTron]], [[Rio Receiver]] and [[Squeezebox (network music player)#SliMP3 .282001.29|SliMP3]] digital media players. An early version of a video-capable digital media player was presented by F.C. Jeng et al. in the International Conf. on Consumer Electronics in 2002.<ref>F.C. Jeng, M. Jeanson, S-Y Zhu, and K. Konstantinides, [https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1013945 \"Design of a home media center with network and streaming capabilities\"], IEEE Intern. Conf. on Consumer Electronics, 2002, pp. 102-103.</ref> It included a network interface card, a media processor for audio and video decoding, an analog video encoder (for video playback to a TV), an audio digital to analog converter for audio playback, and an IR (infrared receiver) for remote-control-interface.\n\nA concept of a digital media player was also introduced by Intel in 2002 at the [[Intel Developer Forum]] as part of their \u201cExtended Wireless PC Initiative.\"  Intel's digital media player was based on an Xscale PXA210 processor and supported 802.11b wireless networking. Intel was among the first to use the Linux embedded operating system and [[UPnP]] technology for its digital media player. Networked audio and DVD players were among the first consumer devices to integrate digital media player functionality. Examples include the Philips [[Streamium]]-range of products that allowed for remote streaming of audio, the GoVideo D2730 Networked DVD player which integrated DVD playback with the capability to stream Rhapsody audio from a PC, and the Buffalo LinkTheater which combined a DVD player with a digital media player.  More recently, the Xbox 360 gaming console from Microsoft was among the first gaming devices that integrated a digital media player. With the Xbox 360, Microsoft also introduced the concept of a [[Windows Media Center Extender]], which allows users to access the Media center capabilities of a PC remotely, through a home network.  More recently, Linksys, D-Link, and HP introduced the latest generation of digital media players that support 720p and 1080p high resolution video playback and may integrate both Windows Extender and traditional digital media player functionality.\n\n==Typical features==\nA digital media player can connect to the home network using either a wireless ([[IEEE 802.11a-1999|IEEE 802.11a]], b, g, and n) or wired [[Ethernet]] connection. Digital media players includes a user interface that allows users to navigate through their digital media library, search for, and play back media files. Some digital media players only handle music; some handle music and pictures; some handle music, pictures, and video; while others go further to allow internet browsing or controlling Live TV from a PC with a TV tuner.\n\nSome other capabilities which are accomplished by digital media players include:\n* Play, catalog, and store local [[hard disk]], [[USB flash drive|flash drive]], or [[memory card]] music [[CD]]s and view CD album art, view digital photos, and watch [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] or other videos.\n* Stream movies, music, photos (media) over the wired or wireless network<ref>{{cite web|title=Airplay|url=https://www.apple.com/airplay/|publisher=apple.com}}</ref>\n* View digital pictures (one by one or as picture [[slideshow]]s)\n* Stream online video to a TV from services such as [[Netflix]] and [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Google TV|url=https://www.google.com/tv/apps.html|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n*Play video games such as [[Angry Birds]] and others.<ref>{{cite web|last=White|first=Charlie|title=Now You Can Play Angry Birds On a Roku 2 [PICS]|url=http://mashable.com/2011/08/06/roku-2-xs-review/|publisher=mashable.com|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n*Browse the Internet, check email and access [[social networking]] sites like [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]], [[LinkedIn]] on TV through downloadable applications.\n*[[Videotelephony|Video conference]] by connecting a [[webcam]] and microphone.<ref name=\"amkette1\"/>\n\nIn the 2010s, there are stand-alone digital media players on the market from AC Ryan, Asus, Apple (e.g., [[Apple TV]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Barlow|first=Graham|title=Apple TV review|url=http://www.techradar.com/reviews/audio-visual/av-accessories/apple-tv-900409/review|publisher=techradar.com|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>), NetGear (e.g., NTV and NeoTV models), Dune, iOmega, [[Logitech]], Pivos Group, Micca, Sybas (Popcorn Hour), [[Amkette EvoTV]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Almeida|first=Aaron|title=Amkette EvoTV Review|url=http://tech2.in.com/reviews/hd-media-players/amkette-evotv-review/323422|publisher=tech2.in.com|accessdate=17 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712161933/http://tech2.in.com/reviews/hd-media-players/amkette-evotv-review/323422|archivedate=12 July 2012}}</ref> D-Link,  EZfetch, [[Fire TV]], [[Android TV]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Greenwald|first=Will|title=Sony Internet Player With Google TV (NSZ-GS7)|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2413422,00.asp|publisher=pcmag.com|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref> Pinnacle, [[Xtreamer]], and [[Roku]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Biddle|first=Sam|title=Roku 3 Review: The New Best Streaming Box|url=https://gizmodo.com/5991159/roku-3-review-the-new-best-streaming-box|publisher=gizmodo.com|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref> just to name a few. The models change frequently, so it is advisable to visit their web sites for current model names.\n\n===Processors===\nThese devices come with low power consumption processors or [[System on a chip|SoC (System on Chip)]] and are most commonly either based on [[MIPS architecture|MIPS]] or [[ARM architecture]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Cortex-A9 Processor|url=http://www.arm.com/products/processors/cortex-a/cortex-a9.php|publisher=arm.com}}</ref> processors combined with integrated [[Digital signal processing|DSP]] [[Graphics processing unit|GPU]] in a [[System on a chip|SoC]] (or [[MPSoC]]) package. They also include [[RAM]]-memory and some type of built-in [[Flash memory|type of non-volatile computer memory (Flash memory)]].<ref name=\"amkette1\">{{cite web|title=Amkette|url=http://amkette.com/product.jsp?id=185|publisher=Amkette|accessdate=17 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524194023/http://amkette.com/product.jsp?id=185|archive-date=24 May 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Internal hard-drive capabilities===\n''HD media player'' or ''HDD media player'' (''HDMP'') is a consumer product that combines digital media player with a [[hard drive]] (HD) [[disk enclosure|enclosure]] with all the hardware and software for playing [[Content (media and publishing)|audio]], [[video]] and photos to a television. All these can play computer-based media files to a television without the need for a separate computer or network connection, and some can even be used as a conventional external hard-drive. These types of digital media players are sometimes sold as empty shells to allow the user to fit their own choice of hard drive (some can manage unlimited hard disk capacity and other only a certain capacity, i.e. 1TB, 2TB, 3TB, or 4TB), and the same model is sometimes sold with or without an internal hard drive already fitted.\n\n=== Formats, resolutions and file systems ===\nDigital media players can usually play [[H.264/MPEG-4 AVC|H.264]] (SD and [[high resolution|HD]]), [[MPEG-4 Part 2]] (SD and HD), [[MPEG-1]], [[MPEG-2]] [[.mpg]], [[MPEG-2]] .[[MPEG transport stream|TS]], [[VOB]] and [[ISO image]]s video, with [[Pulse-code modulation|PCM]], [[MP3]] and [[Dolby AC-3|AC3]] audio tracks. They can also display images (such as [[JPEG]] and [[Portable Network Graphics|PNG]]) and play music files (such as [[FLAC]], [[MP3]] and [[Ogg]]).\n\n===Operating system===\n{{main|List of smart TV platforms and middleware software}}\nWhile most media players have traditionally been running [[Proprietary software|proprietary]] or [[Open-source model|open source]] [[software framework]]s versions based [[Linux]] as their operating systems, many newer network connected media players are based on the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] platform which gives them an advantage in terms of applications and games from the [[Google Play]] store. Even without Android some digital media players still have the ability to run applications (sometimes available via an 'app store' [[digital distribution]] [[platform (computing)|platform]]), interactive on-demand media, personalized communications, and social networking features<ref>{{cite web|author= Devindra Hardawar |url=https://venturebeat.com/2010/12/08/why-your-tv-is-the-new-app-battleground/ |title=Why your TV is the new app battleground |publisher=Venturebeat.com |date=8 December 2010 |accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10132877 BBC News&nbsp;\u2013 Google launches smart TV service]. bbc.co.uk (20 May 2010). Retrieved on 11 November 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Stan Schroeder 230 |url=http://mashable.com/2010/05/17/google-intel-sony-smart-tv/ |title=Google, Intel and Sony to Introduce Smart TV |publisher=Mashable.com |date=17 May 2010 |accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialtimes.com/2010/05/opinion-will-googles-smart-tv-finally-bring-apps-and-web-browsing-to-the-living-room/ |title=Opinion: Will Google's Smart TV Finally Bring Apps and Web Browsing To The Living Room? |publisher=Socialtimes.com |date=17 May 2010 |accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10132877 |title=Google launches smart TV service |publisher=BBC |date=20 May 2010 |accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Connections ==\n[[File:Dighub3.jpg|thumb|300px|An example of a Digital media player in a network]]\nThere are two ways to connect an extender to its central [[Home theater PC|media center]] or [[HTPC]] server - wired, or wireless. A wireless connection can be established between the media extender and its central media center. On the downside, interference may cause a \"less than optimal\" connection and cause network congestion, resulting in stuttering sound, missing frames from video, and other anomalies. It is recommended{{By whom|date=September 2013}} that an [[802.11a]] or better be used, and over as short of a distance as possible.\n[[File:Digital media receiver - network music player.jpg|thumb|A wireless media extender from [[Arctic (company)|Arctic]] for music streaming and multi-room entertainment<ref>[http://www.arctic.ac/en/p/living/multi-room-system/463/audio-relay.html?c=2327 \"Audio Relay\"] Retrieved 11 October 2012</ref>]]\n\n===Streaming and communication protocols===\nWhile early digital media players used proprietary communication protocols to interface with media servers, today most digital media players either use standard-based protocols such [[Server Message Block|SMB/CIFS/SAMBA]] or [[Network File System|NFS]], or rely on some version of [[UPnP]] (Universal Plug and Play) and [[DLNA]] (Digital Living Network Alliance) standards. DLNA-compliant digital media players and Media Servers is meant to guarantee a minimum set of functionality and proper interoperability among digital media players and servers regardless of the manufacturer, but unfortunately not every manufacturer follows the standards perfectly which can lead to incompatibility.\n\n===Media server===\nSome digital media players will only connect to specific media server software installed on a PC to stream music, pictures and recorded or live TV originating from the computer. Apple iTunes can, for example, be used this way with the Apple TV hardware that connects to a TV. Apple has developed a tightly integrated device and content management ecosystem with their [[iTunes Store]], personal computers, [[iOS (Apple)|iOS]] [[List of iOS devices|devices]], and the [[AppleTV]] [[digital media receiver]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2010/10/01/how-apple-took-the-high-ground-in-the-battle-for-the-global-digital-living-room/ | title=How Apple took the high ground in the battle for the global digital living room | first=Philip | last=Elmer-DeWitt | date=1 October 2010 | publisher=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] | accessdate=13 February 2011}}</ref>  The most recent version of the AppleTV, at $99, has lost the hard-drive that was included in its predecessor and fully depends on either streaming internet content, or another computer on the home network for media.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bostonherald.com/business/technology/reviews/view/20110124apples_web_tv_packs_big_bang_for_the_buck/srvc=home&position=also | title=Apple's Web TV packs big bang for the buck | first=Brendan| last=Lynch | date=24 January 2011 | publisher=[[Boston Herald]] | accessdate=8 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Connection ports===\n[[File:Apple TV. 1st generation-2290.jpg|thumb|Back of 1st generation Apple TV]]\n[[File:Apple TV 2nd Generation back.jpg|thumb|Back of 2nd &amp; 3rd generation Apple TV]]\nTelevision connection is usually done via; composite, [[SCART]], Component, [[HDMI]] video, with Optical Audio (TOSLINK/SPDIF), and connect to the local network and [[broadband]] internet using either a wired [[Ethernet]] or a wireless [[Wi-Fi]] connection, and some also have built-in [[Bluetooth]] support for remotes and game-pads or joysticks. Some players come with [[USB]] ([[USB 2.0]] or [[USB 3.0]]) ports which allow local media content playback.\n\n== Use ==\n=== Market impact on traditional television services ===\nThe convergence of content, technology, and broadband access allows consumers to stream television shows and movies to their high-definition television in competition with [[pay television]] providers. The research company SNL Kagan expects 12 million households, roughly 10%, to go without cable, satellite or telco video service by 2015 using [[Over-the-top content|Over The Top]] services.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://blogs.forbes.com/dorothypomerantz/2011/07/20/12-million-households-expected-to-cut-the-cord-by-2015 | title=12 Million Households Expected to Cut the Cord By 2015 | date=20 July 2011 | work=[[Forbes]] | accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> This represents a new trend in the broadcast television industry, as the list of options for watching movies and TV over the Internet grows at a rapid pace. Research also shows that even as traditional television service providers are trimming their customer base, they are adding [[Broadband]] Internet customers. Nearly 76.6 million U.S. households get broadband from leading cable and telephone companies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leichtmanresearch.com/press/051711release.html |title=Nearly 1.3 Million Add Broadband in the First Quarter of 2011 |date=17 May 2011 |publisher=Leichtman Research Group |accessdate=17 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713200733/http://www.leichtmanresearch.com/press/051711release.html |archivedate=13 July 2011 }}</ref> although only a portion have sufficient speeds to support quality video steaming.<ref name=Forrester>{{cite web | url=http://www.forrester.com/rb/Research/online_video_on_tv_leads_to_cord-cutting/q/id/57160/t/2/ | title=Online Video On TV Leads To Cord-Cutting By 2012 | first=James L. | last=McQuivey, Ph.D. | date=14 March 2011 | publisher=[[Forrester Research]] | accessdate=22 July 2011}}</ref> Convergence devices for home entertainment will likely play a much larger role in the future of broadcast television, effectively shifting traditional revenue streams while providing consumers with more options.<ref name=Forrester/>\n\nAccording to a report from the researcher NPD In-Stat, only about 12 million U.S. households have their either Web-capable TVs or digital media players connected to the Internet, although In-Stat estimates about 25 million U.S. TV households own a set with the built-in network capability. Also, In-Stat predicts that 100 million homes in North America and western Europe will own digital media players and television sets that blend traditional programs with Internet content by 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2012/03/100-million-tvs-will-be-internet-connected-by-2016.html|title=100 million TVs will be Internet-connected by 2016|work=latimes.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Use for illegal streaming ===\nSince at least 2015,<ref name=\"engadget-sellerskodi\">{{cite web|title=Kodi takes the fight to sellers of pirate TV boxes|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/02/14/kodi-takes-the-fight-to-sellers-of-pirate-tv-boxes/|website=Engadget|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"tf-kodiban\">{{cite web|title=Amazon Bans Kodi/XBMC App Over Piracy Concerns|url=https://torrentfreak.com/amazon-bans-kodi-app-over-piracy-concerns-150616/|website=TorrentFreak|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"techhive-amazon\">{{cite web|title=Amazon pulls popular video app Kodi from its store, blames piracy|url=http://www.techhive.com/article/2937028/amazon-pulls-popular-video-app-kodi-from-its-store-blames-piracy.html|website=TechHive|publisher=IDG|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"tf-firestickuk\">{{cite web|title=Did Pirates Clean Out Amazon Fire TV Stock in the UK?|url=https://torrentfreak.com/did-pirates-clean-out-amazon-fire-tv-stock-in-the-uk-151229/|website=TorrentFreak|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> dealers have marketed digital media players, often running the Android operating system and branded as being \"'''fully-loaded'''\", that are promoted as offering free streaming access to copyrighted media content, including films and television programs, as well as [[Pirate decryption|live feeds of television channels]]. These players are commonly bundled with the open source media player software [[Kodi (software)|Kodi]], which is in turn pre-loaded with [[Plug-in (computing)|plug-ins]] enabling access to services streaming this content without the permission of their respective copyright holders. These \"fully-loaded\" set-top boxes are often sold through online marketplaces such as [[Amazon.com]] and [[eBay]], as well as local retailers.<ref name=\"cbc-freetv\"/><ref name=\"ars-fullyloadedkodi\" /> The spread of these players has been attributed to their ease of use (with user experiences similar to legal subscription services such as [[Netflix]]) and low cost, as well as the content that is offered from the services pre-installed on the boxes.<ref name=\"ars-fullyloadedkodi\">{{cite web|title=Kodi: Open source TV app inspires full-blown copyright panic in the UK|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/05/kodi-fully-loaded-boxes-are-they-legal/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"cbc-pirateboxes\">{{cite web|title='Free TV' Android boxes finding their way into many Canadian households, study says|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/piracy-android-box-free-tv-1.4098249|website=CBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"cbc-freetv\">{{cite web|title=Free TV for life? It's here, and it may even be legal|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/android-box-streaming-1.3455524|website=CBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"Fully-loaded\" set-top boxes have been subject to legal controversies, especially noting that their user experiences made them accessible to end-users who may not always realize that they are actually streaming pirated content.<ref name=\"ars-fullyloadedkodi\" /><ref name=\"cbc-pirateboxes\" /> In the United Kingdom, the [[Federation Against Copyright Theft]] (FACT) has taken court actions on behalf of rightsholders against those who market digital media players pre-loaded with access to copyrighted content. In January 2017, an individual seller plead not guilty to charges of marketing and distributing devices that [[Anti-circumvention|circumvent]] [[technological protection measures]].<ref name=\"bbc-notguilty\">{{cite web|title=Not guilty plea in landmark Kodi box trial|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-38769045|website=BBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc-fullyloadedtest\">{{cite web|title=Sale of Kodi 'fully-loaded' streaming boxes faces legal test|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-37474595|website=BBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"arsuk-fivearrests\">{{cite web|title=Five suspects arrested for sale of \"fully loaded\" Kodi streaming boxes|url=https://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2017/02/five-suspects-arrested-for-sale-of-fully-loaded-kodi-streaming-boxes/|website=Ars Technica UK|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, the [[High Court of Justice]] ruled that [[BT Group]], [[Sky plc]], [[TalkTalk TV|TalkTalk]], and [[Virgin Media]] must block servers that had been used on such set-top boxes to illegally stream [[Premier League]] football games.<ref name=\"ars-kodicrackdown\">{{cite web|title=Kodi crackdown: Premier League wins High Court order to block illegal streams|url=https://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2017/03/kodi-crackdown-premier-league-high-court-order-block-illegal-streams/|website=Ars Technica UK|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> Later in the month, [[Amazon UK]] banned the sale of \"certain media players\" that had been pre-loaded with software to illegally stream copyrighted content.<ref name=\"arsuk-amazonban\">{{cite web|title=Amazon bans \"certain\" media streamers, but are Kodi-loaded boxes barred?|url=https://arstechnica.co.uk/gadgets/2017/04/amazon-uk-kodi-media-streamer-ban/|website=Ars Technica UK|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> On 26 April 2017, the [[European Court of Justice]] ruled that the distribution of set-top boxes with access to unauthorized streams of copyrighted works violated the exclusive rights to communicate them to the public.<ref name=\"ars-fullyloadedkodi\"/> In September 2017, a British seller of such boxes pled guilty to violations of the [[Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988|Copyright, Designs and Patents Act]] for selling devices that can circumvent effective [[technical protection measures]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/landmark-kodi-trial-dissolved-due-to-guilty-plea/|title=Landmark loaded Kodi box trial dissolves with guilty plea|last=Osborne|first=Charlie|work=ZDNet|access-date=26 September 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn Canada, it was initially believed that these set-top boxes fell within a legal grey area, as the transient nature of streaming content did not necessarily mean that the content was being downloaded in violation of [[Canadian copyright law]].<ref name=\"cbc-freetv\"/> However, on 1 June 2016, a consortium of Canadian media companies ([[BCE Inc.]], [[Rogers Communications]], and [[Videotron]]) obtained a temporary federal injunction against five retailers of Android-based set-top boxes, alleging that their continued sale were causing \"irreparable harm\" to their television businesses, and that the devices' primary purpose were to facilitate copyright infringement. The court rejected an argument by one of the defendants, who stated that they were only marketing a hardware device with publicly available software, ruling that the defendants were \"deliberately encourag[ing] consumers and potential clients to circumvent authorized ways of accessing content.\"<ref name=\"cbc-freetvcourt\"/><ref name=\"cbc-freetvcourt\">{{cite web|title=Cable companies launch court battle against 'free TV' Android box vendors|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/free-tv-loaded-android-box-cable-1.3633331|website=CBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> 11 additional defendants were subsequently added to the suit. The lawyer of one of the defendants argued that retailers should not be responsible for the actions of their users, as any type of computing device could theoretically be used for legal or illegal purposes.<ref name=\"cbc-moredefendants\">{{cite web|title=Cable companies take more Android box dealers to court to stamp out 'free TV'|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/free-tv-android-box-cable-companies-challenge-1.3660656|website=CBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> In April 2017, the [[Federal Court of Appeal]] blocked an appeal requesting that the injunction be lifted pending the outcome of the case.<ref name=\"cbc-boxappeal\">{{cite web|title='Free TV' Android box dealers lose court appeal to lift sales ban|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/android-box-free-tv-bell-rogers-1.4033741|website=CBC News|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the software is free to use, the developers of Kodi have not endorsed any add-on or Kodi-powered device intended for facilitating copyright infringement.  Nathan Betzen, president of the XBMC Foundation (the non-profit organization which oversees the development of the Kodi software), argued that the reputation of Kodi had been harmed by third-party retailers who \"make a quick buck modifying Kodi, installing broken piracy add-ons, advertising that Kodi lets you watch free movies and TV, and then vanishing when the user buys the box and finds out that the add-on they were sold on was a crummy, constantly breaking mess.\" Betzen stated that the XBMC Foundation was willing to enforce its [[trademark]]s against those who use them to promote Kodi-based products which facilitate copyright infringement.<ref name=\"tf-legalaction\">{{cite web|title=Kodi Announces Legal Action to Smash Piracy Links|url=https://torrentfreak.com/kodi-announces-legal-action-to-smash-piracy-links-160215/|website=TorrentFreak|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"engadget-sellerskodi\"/>\n\nFollowing a lawsuit by [[Dish Network]] against TVAddons, a website that offered streaming add-ons that were often used with Kodi and on such devices, in June 2017, the group shut down its add-ons and website. A technology analyst speculated that the service could eventually re-appear under a different name in the future, as have [[torrent tracker]]s.<ref name=\"cbc-dishlawsuit\">{{cite web|title=Streaming apps for 'free TV' Android box disappear following U.S. lawsuit threat|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/streaming-box-lawsuit-tvaddons-1.4165325?|website=CBC News|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> In June, the service's operator was also sued by the Bell/Rogers/Videotron consortium for inducing copyright infringement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://torrentfreak.com/tvaddons-returns-ugly-war-canadian-telcos-kodi-addons-170801/|title=TVAddons Returns, But in Ugly War With Canadian Telcos Over Kodi Addons - TorrentFreak|date=1 August 2017|work=TorrentFreak|access-date=2 August 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, [[Televisa]] was granted a court order banning the sale of all [[Roku]] products in Mexico, as it was alleged that third-parties had been operating subscription television services for the devices that contain unlicensed content. The content is streamed through unofficial apps that are added to the devices through hacking. Roku objected to the allegations, stating that these services were not certified by the company or part of its official Channels platform, whose terms of service require that they have rights to stream the content that they offer. Roku also stated that it actively cooperates with reports of channels that infringe copyrights.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/roku-sales-banned-mexico-piracy-1202484188/|title=Roku Device Sales Banned in Mexico Over Piracy|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=30 June 2017|work=Variety|access-date=3 July 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> The ruling was overturned in October 2018 after Roku took additional steps to remove channels with unauthorized content from the platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2018/10/17/17989598/roku-devices-mexico-sales-back-piracy-concerns-court-ruling-streaming|title=Roku devices are coming back to Mexico after court ruling|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=2018-10-17|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] sent letters to the CEOs of [[Amazon.com]] and [[eBay]], asking for their help in removing such devices from their marketplaces. The letter cited malware risks, fraudulent use of FCC certification marks, and how their distribution through major online marketplaces may incorrectly suggest that they are legal and legitimate products.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/05/29/fcc-asks-amazon-and-ebay-to-stop-selling-fake-pay-tv-boxes/|title=FCC asks Amazon and eBay to stop selling fake pay TV boxes |website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-30}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Television}}\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Comparison of digital media players]]\n*[[Cord-cutting]]\n*[[Digital Living Network Alliance]]\n*[[Digital video recorder]]\n*[[List of net-connected media players]]\n*[[List of smart TV platforms and middleware software]]\n*[[Second screen]]\n*[[Streaming media]]\n*[[System on a chip]]\n*[[Tivoization]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100315162703/http://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/reviews/4243711.html?page=7 HP MediaSmart Connect Wins Popular Mechanics Editor's Choice Award at CES 2008]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070820040205/http://reviews.cnet.com/4323-6531_7-6509113.html CNET Editors' Best Network Music Players]\n*[https://www.pcmag.com/category2/0,1874,924250,00.asp PC Magazine Media Hub & Receiver Finder]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130528013354/http://www.audiofi.co.uk/reviews/index.php AudioFi Reviews of wireless players]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080430135734/http://www.pcworld.com/article/id,108818-page,1-c,plugandplay/article.html PC World's Future Gear: PC on the HiFi, and the TV]\n\n{{Home theater PC (application software)}}\n{{Media player (application software)}}\n\n[[Category:Digital media players| ]]\n[[Category:Digital media receivers| ]]\n[[Category:Consumer electronics]]\n[[Category:Media players]]\n[[Category:Networking hardware]]\n[[Category:Television technology]]\n[[Category:Multimedia]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) devices]]\n[[Category:Digital audio]]\n", "name_user": "154.157.177.243", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_media_player"}
{"title_page": "Billy Hibbert", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|          name      = Billy Hibbert\n|               image = \n|            fullname = William Hibbert\n|         birth_date = {{birth date|1884|9|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Golborne]], England\n|         death_date = {{death date and age|1949|3|16|1884|9|21|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Blackpool]], England\n|              height = \n|            position = [[Striker (association football)|Centre Forward]]\n| youthyears1 =   \n| youthclubs1 =   Golborne Juniors\n|  years1 =    \n| years2 =   \n| years3 =  1906\u20131911 \n| years4 =  1911\u20131920 \n| years5 =   \n| years6 =   \n| years7 =  1920\u20131922 \n| years8 =  1922 \n| years9 =  1923 \n| years10 =  1923\u20131926 \n| years11 =   \n| years12 =  1927\n|  clubs1 =   Newton-le-Willows \n| clubs2 =  Bryn Central \n| clubs3 =  [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] \n| clubs4 =  [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] \n| clubs5 =  \u2192 [[Sheffield Wednesday]] (guest) \n| clubs6 =  \u2192 [[Leeds City F.C.|Leeds City]] (guest) \n| clubs7 =  [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] \n| clubs8 =  [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] \n| clubs9 =  [[Fall River Marksmen]] \n| clubs10 =  [[J&P Coats]] \n| clubs11 =  Burscough Rangers \n| clubs12 =  [[Real Gimn\u00e1stico CF]] \n| caps1 =             \n| caps2 =   \n| caps3 =  178  \n| caps4 =  139  \n| caps5 =   \n| caps6 =    0   \n| caps7 =   53  \n| caps8 =   16   \n| caps9 =    4   \n| caps10 =   56  \n| goals1 =  \n| goals2 =  \n| goals3 =  99  \n| goals4 =  46  \n| goals5 =  \n| goals6 =  0  \n| goals7 =  26  \n| goals8 =  4  \n| goals9 =  1  \n| goals10 =  24 \n| nationalyears1 =   1910\n| nationalteam1 =   [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps1 =    1  \n| nationalgoals1 =   0 \n}}\n'''William Hibbert''' (21 September 1884 \u2013 16 March 1949) was a professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as [[Striker (association football)|centre forward]] and was [[cap (sport)|capped]] once for [[England national football team|England]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Golborne]], [[Lancashire]], England, Hibbert started playing at school before beginning his amateur career first at Newton le Willows then Bryn Central. On 3 May 1906, he turned professional with [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Bury F.C.|Bury]]<ref name=\"Colin\">{{cite book | last = Jose | first = Colin | title = American Soccer League, 1921-1931 | type = Hardback | publisher = The Scarecrow Press | year = 1998 | id = ({{ISBN|0-8108-3429-4}}) }}</ref> In 1911, he signed with [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] for a then record fee.<ref>Newcastle United - a statistical history [http://www.khscott.org.uk/nufc/template_player.php?thisPage=1&totalRows=155&pid=351 Billy Hibbert]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He played 139 league games scoring 46 goals either side of the [[World War I|First World War]] &mdash; during which time he guested for both [[Sheffield Wednesday]] and [[Leeds City F.C.|Leeds City]].<ref name=\"Colin\"/>  He also played four games as a guest for [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] in the 1916\u201317 season.<ref>{{cite book|first=Ray|last=Simpson|title=The Clarets Chronicles: The Definitive History of Burnley Football Club|year=2007|isbn=978-0-9557468-0-2|page=489}}</ref> In 1920 he signed for [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] where he was the club's top goal-scorer in its final two seasons in [[Football League First Division|Division One]].<ref name=\"frost\">{{cite book\n| last = Frost\n| first = Terry\n| title = Bradford City A Complete Record 1903-1988\n| publisher = Breedon Books Sport\n| year = 1988\n| isbn = 0-907969-38-0}}</ref> When he left City after it was relegated, he had scored 26 goals in 53 games. He then signed for [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]].\n\nIn 1923, he moved to the United States where he joined the [[Fall River Marksmen]] of the [[American Soccer League (1921-1933)|American Soccer League]]. He saw time in only four league games before moving to [[J&P Coats]] for the remainder of the season, continuing with Coats through the end of the 1925\u201326 season. He also spent time in June 1927 with [[Real Gimn\u00e1stico CF]].<ref name=\"Colin\"/>\n\n==National team==\nHe also won one international [[cap (sport)|cap]] for [[England national football team|England]] against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] on 2 April 1910 in a 2\u20130 defeat.\n\n==Manager==\nAfter his playing career finished he was a coach in the [[United States of America]], Spain and at [[Wigan Borough F.C.|Wigan Borough]]. He died in [[Blackpool]], England, on 16 March 1949.\n\n==Personal life==\nHis brother-in-law was [[Joe Shaw (footballer born 1883)|Joe Shaw]] who played more than 300 games for [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2007}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{englandstats|473}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hibbert, Billy}}\n[[Category:1884 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Golborne]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Bury F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Oldham Athletic A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:American Soccer League (1921\u20131933) players]]\n[[Category:Fall River Marksmen players]]\n[[Category:J&P Coats players]]\n[[Category:Levante UD footballers]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. wartime guest players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. wartime guest players]]\n[[Category:English Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|          name      = Billy Hibbert\n|               image = \n|            fullname = William Hibbert\n|         birth_date = {{birth date|1884|9|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Golborne]], England\n|         death_date = {{death date and age|1949|3|16|1884|9|21|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Blackpool]], England\n|              height = \n|            position = [[Striker (association football)|Centre Forward]]\n| youthyears1 =   \n| youthclubs1 =   Golborne Juniors\n|  years1 =    \n| years2 =   \n| years3 =  1906\u20131911 \n| years4 =  1911\u20131920 \n| years5 =   \n| years6 =   \n| years7 =  1920\u20131922 \n| years8 =  1922 \n| years9 =  1923 \n| years10 =  1923\u20131926 \n| years11 =   \n| years12 =  1927\n|  clubs1 =   Newton-le-Willows \n| clubs2 =  Bryn Central \n| clubs3 =  [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] \n| clubs4 =  [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] \n| clubs5 =  \u2192 [[Sheffield Wednesday]] (guest) \n| clubs6 =  \u2192 [[Leeds City F.C.|Leeds City]] (guest) \n| clubs7 =  [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] \n| clubs8 =  [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] \n| clubs9 =  [[Fall River Marksmen]] \n| clubs10 =  [[J&P Coats]] \n| clubs11 =  Burscough Rangers \n| clubs12 =  [[Real Gimn\u00e1stico CF]] \n| caps1 =             \n| caps2 =   \n| caps3 =  178  \n| caps4 =  139  \n| caps5 =   \n| caps6 =    0   \n| caps7 =   53  \n| caps8 =   16   \n| caps9 =    4   \n| caps10 =   56  \n| goals1 =  \n| goals2 =  \n| goals3 =  99  \n| goals4 =  46  \n| goals5 =  \n| goals6 =  0  \n| goals7 =  26  \n| goals8 =  4  \n| goals9 =  1  \n| goals10 =  24 \n| nationalyears1 =   1910\n| nationalteam1 =   [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps1 =    1  \n| nationalgoals1 =   0 \n}}\n'''William Hibbert''' (21 September 1884 \u2013 16 March 1949) was a professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as [[Striker (association football)|centre forward]] and was [[cap (sport)|capped]] once for [[England national football team|England]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Golborne]], [[Lancashire]], England, Hibbert started playing at school before beginning his amateur career first at Newton le Willows then Bryn Central. On 3 May 1906, he turned professional with [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Bury F.C.]]<ref name=\"Colin\">{{cite book | last = Jose | first = Colin | title = American Soccer League, 1921-1931 | type = Hardback | publisher = The Scarecrow Press | year = 1998 | id = ({{ISBN|0-8108-3429-4}}) }}</ref>  In 1911, he signed with [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] for a then record fee.<ref>Newcastle United - a statistical history [http://www.khscott.org.uk/nufc/template_player.php?thisPage=1&totalRows=155&pid=351 Billy Hibbert]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He played 139 league games scoring 46 goals either side of the [[World War I|First World War]] &mdash; during which time he guested for both [[Sheffield Wednesday]] and [[Leeds City F.C.|Leeds City]].<ref name=\"Colin\"/>  He also played four games as a guest for [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] in the 1916\u201317 season.<ref>{{cite book|first=Ray|last=Simpson|title=The Clarets Chronicles: The Definitive History of Burnley Football Club|year=2007|isbn=978-0-9557468-0-2|page=489}}</ref>  In 1920 he signed for [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] where he was the club's top goal-scorer in its final two seasons in [[Football League First Division|Division One]].<ref name=\"frost\">{{cite book\n| last = Frost\n| first = Terry\n| title = Bradford City A Complete Record 1903-1988\n| publisher = Breedon Books Sport\n| year = 1988\n| isbn = 0-907969-38-0}}</ref> When he left City after it was relegated, he had scored 26 goals in 53 games.  He then signed for [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]].\n\nIn 1923, he moved to the United States where he joined the [[Fall River Marksmen]] of the [[American Soccer League (1921-1933)|American Soccer League]]. He saw time in only four league games before moving to [[J&P Coats]] for the remainder of the season, continuing with Coats through the end of the 1925\u201326 season. He also spent time in June 1927 with [[Real Gimn\u00e1stico CF]].<ref name=\"Colin\"/>\n\n==National team==\nHe also won one international [[cap (sport)|cap]] for [[England national football team|England]] against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] on 2 April 1910 in a 2\u20130 defeat.\n\n==Manager==\nAfter his playing career finished he was a coach in the [[United States of America]], Spain and at [[Wigan Borough F.C.|Wigan Borough]]. He died in [[Blackpool]], England, on 16 March 1949.\n\n==Personal life==\nHis brother-in-law was [[Joe Shaw (footballer born 1883)|Joe Shaw]] who played more than 300 games for [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2007}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{englandstats|473}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hibbert, Billy}}\n[[Category:1884 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Golborne]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Bury F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Oldham Athletic A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:American Soccer League (1921\u20131933) players]]\n[[Category:Fall River Marksmen players]]\n[[Category:J&P Coats players]]\n[[Category:Levante UD footballers]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. wartime guest players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. wartime guest players]]\n[[Category:English Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[