n August 2000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themillers.co.uk/staticFiles/87/1b/0,,10360~7047,00.doc |title=Past Players |publisher=Rotherham United F.C. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810044511/http://www.themillers.co.uk/staticFiles/87/1b/0%2C%2C10360~7047%2C00.doc |archivedate=10 August 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Durkin, Billy}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rotherham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aldershot F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Weymouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n\n{{England-footy-forward-1920s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Durkin"}
{"title_page": "Billy Clarke (footballer, born 1987)", "text_new": "{{about|the Irish forward born in 1987|the former Ipswich midfielder|Billy Clark (footballer, born 1991)}}\n{{short description|Irish footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{similar names|William Clarke (disambiguation){{!}}William Clarke}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name            = Billy Clarke\n| image           =\n| caption         =\n| fullname        = William Charles Clarke<ref>{{Hugman|22596|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1987|12|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Cork (city)|Cork]], Ireland\n| currentclub     = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]\n| clubnumber      = 16\n| height          = {{convert|1.7|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position        = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1     = {{0|0000}}\u20132005 | youthclubs1 = [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n| years1          = 2005\u20132009 | clubs1 = [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]                    | caps1 = 49  | goals1 = 3\n| years2          = 2006      | clubs2 = \u2192 [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] (loan) | caps2 = 6   | goals2 = 0\n| years3          = 2008      | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] (loan)                     | caps3 = 8   | goals3 = 1\n| years4          = 2008      | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] (loan)               | caps4 = 20  | goals4 = 8\n| years5          = 2009      | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] (loan)   | caps5 = 5   | goals5 = 3\n| years6          = 2009      | clubs6 = \u2192 [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] (loan)                 | caps6 = 8   | goals6 = 6\n| years7          = 2009\u20132012 | clubs7 = [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]                          | caps7 = 27  | goals7 = 1\n| years8          = 2011      | clubs8 =  \u2192 [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] (loan)  | caps8 = 6   | goals8 = 1\n| years9          = 2012\u20132014 | clubs9 = [[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]]                    | caps9 = 82  | goals9 = 20\n| years10         = 2014\u20132017 | clubs10 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]               | caps10 = 98 | goals10 = 24\n| years11         = 2017\u20132019     | clubs11 = [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]     | caps11 = 17 | goals11 = 1\n| years12         = 2019  | clubs12 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]                   | caps12 = 14 | goals12 = 1\n| years13         = 2019\u20132020  | clubs13 = [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]                | caps13 = 9  | goals13 = 0\n| years14         = 2020\u2013  | clubs14 = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]                | caps14 = 10 | goals14 = 2\n| nationalyears1  = 2003 | nationalteam1 = [[Republic of Ireland national under-17 football team|Republic of Ireland U17]] | nationalcaps1 = 2 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2  = 2005\u20132006 | nationalteam2 = [[Republic of Ireland national under-19 football team|Republic of Ireland U19]] | nationalcaps2 = 8 | nationalgoals2 = 6\n| nationalyears3  = 2007\u20132008 | nationalteam3 = [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland U21]] | nationalcaps3 = 11 | nationalgoals3 = 1\n| club-update     = 09:33, 17 May 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''William Charles Clarke''' (born 13 December 1987) is an Irish [[association football|footballer]] who plays for [[EFL League Two|League Two]] club [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]. He plays as midfield and striker and has played for Ireland at various levels up to [[Republic of Ireland under-21 national football team|under-21]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Ipswich Town===\nBorn in [[Cork (city)|Cork]], Clarke is a product of the [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] Academy and signed professional for the club in May 2005. He made his professional d\u00e9but as a substitute against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] in late November 2005. He won the [[Irish Examiner]] Junior Sports Star of the year award for Soccer in 2005 and was nominated for the Irish Under-19 Player of the Year award in 2006. He also made a big contribution to Ipswich's youth team in winning the [[FA Youth Cup]] in 2005.\n\nAt the end of the 2005\u201306 season he was sent on loan to [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] to gain first team experience, playing six league games. During the January 2008 transfer window, he joined Scottish side [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] on loan. He scored his first goal, a late winner, in a crucial match against [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/7296111.stm\n|title=Inverness CT 0\u20131 Falkirk\n|publisher=BBC\n|date=15 March 2008 |accessdate=29 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nAfter returning to Ipswich Clarke scored his first league goal in the 2\u20131 victory over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and followed it up three days later with the winning goal in the 2\u20131 victory over [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]. He also scored in a 3\u20131 victory over [[Essex]] side, [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]].\n\nClarke was transfer-listed and on 8 August 2008 went to [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] on one month's loan, which was extended to January 2009. He scored four times against [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] on 30 August 2008. He also scored a vital goal in the [[Football League Cup|Carling Cup]] against [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]], knocking the [[Football League One|League One]] side out of the cup.\n\nHe joined [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] on a month's loan in January 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/northampton_town/7840721.stm|title=Cobblers sign Ipswich striker|date=20 January 2009|accessdate=24 January 2009|publisher=[[bbc.co.uk]]}}</ref> He scored a hat-trick on his debut in a 5\u20131 victory over [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]. It was the first hat-trick scored by a ''Cobblers'' player since 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/7842906.stm|title=Northampton 5\u20131 Crewe|date=24 January 2009|accessdate=24 January 2009|publisher=[[bbc.co.uk]]}}</ref>\n\nClarke joined [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] on loan in the run-in to their attempt to win promotion out of [[Football League Two|League Two]]. He was recruited mainly to cover for the absence of fellow Ipswich loanee [[Jordan Rhodes]], who was injured. Clarke scored his first goal for ''the Bees'' in the 1\u20131 draw at [[Bradford City F.C.|Bradford City]]. He ended his loan spell scoring six goals in eight games. While at Brentford, he scored twice against former club Darlington in the game that Brentford clinched the league two title. He had scored 18 goals overall during his three loan spells that season with Darlington, Northampton and Brentford. He was nominated twice during the season for the League Two Player of the Month.\n\nClarke was released by new Ipswich manager [[Roy Keane]] on 8 May 2009.\n\n===Blackpool===\nOn 26 June 2009, Clarke signed for fellow [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] on a two-year contract with an option for a further year; his contract starting on 1 July, once his Ipswich contract expired.<ref name=\"bfc1703917\">{{cite news|url=http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10432~1703917,00.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229161132/http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10432~1703917%2C00.html|archivedate=29 February 2012|title=Clarke set to become Ollie's First Signing|date=26 June 2009|publisher=[[Blackpool F.C.]]|accessdate=26 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Clarke said of the move, \"It happened very quickly. I met the manager ([[Ian Holloway]]) on Tuesday and I had my medical this morning. I am delighted to be here and I can't wait for the season to start,\" adding \"It is brilliant for me to be still playing in the Championship.<ref name=\"bfc1704035\">{{cite news|url=http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10432~1704035,00.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229161145/http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10432~1704035%2C00.html|archivedate=29 February 2012|title=We Speak To Billy Clarke|date=26 June 2009|publisher=[[Blackpool F.C.]]|accessdate=26 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHis first game for ''the Seasiders'' was a pre-season [[exhibition game|friendly]] against [[non-league football|non-league]] side [[Burscough F.C.|Burscough]] on 11 July. Two days later he scored the second goal as Blackpool beat [[Barnstaple Town F.C.|Barnstaple Town]] 5\u20130 in a 2009 [[South West Challenge Cup]] group stage match.<ref name=\"bfc1721460\">{{cite news|url=http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10432~1721460,00.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229161157/http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10432~1721460%2C00.html|archivedate=29 February 2012|title=Seasiders Begin With Victory|date=13 July 2009|publisher=[[Blackpool F.C.]]|accessdate=14 July 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August Clarke made his league d\u00e9but as a 73rd-minute substitute as Blackpool started the 2009\u201310 season with a 1\u20131 draw with [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] at [[Loftus Road]]. He scored his first goal for ''the Seasiders'' in a 4\u20133 defeat to [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] at the [[Britannia Stadium]] in the [[2009\u201310 Football League Cup#First round|third round]] of the [[2009\u201310 Football League Cup|2009\u201310]] [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] on 22 September.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/8256916.stm\n|title=Stoke 4 \u2013 3 Blackpool\n|publisher=BBC\n|date=22 September 2009 |accessdate=29 May 2010}}</ref> His first league start came in the 2\u20130 win over [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] at [[Bloomfield Road]] on 17 October. His first league goal came after just 23 seconds of the [[West Lancashire derby]] 1\u20131 draw with [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] on 30 November.<ref name=\"bbc8377127\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/8377127.stm|title=Blackpool V Preston|date=30 November 2009|publisher=[[bbc.co.uk]]|accessdate=30 November 2009}}</ref> He also won the [[Sky Sports]] \"Man of the Match\" award for his performance.<ref name=\"skysports\">{{cite episode| title = Blackpool v Preston \u2013 live | series = Monday Night Live | network = [[Sky Sports]]| location = [[Blackpool]]| airdate = 30 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nAfter three months out through injury, Clarke made his return to action as a 78th-minute substitute in the 1\u20130 home win over his former club Ipswich Town on 6 March 2010.<ref name=\"bfc47457\">{{cite news|url=http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10432~47457,00.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609120929/http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0%2C%2C10432~47457%2C00.html|archivedate=9 June 2012|title=Blackpool vs Ipswich Town|date=6 March 2010|publisher=[[Blackpool F.C.]]|accessdate=6 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> During pre-season for the [[2010\u201311 Blackpool F.C. season|2010\u201311]] season, which was Blackpool's d\u00e9but in the [[Premier League]], Clarke suffered a knee injury that would, it was initially thought, keep him out of action for three months; however, on 26 July it was revealed that Clarke had ruptured his right anterior cruciate ligament and could miss the whole campaign.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120614034602/http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10432~2102593%2C00.html \"FURTHER CLARKE BLOW FOR SEASIDERS\"] \u2013 Blackpool F.C.'s official website</ref> This was confirmed when, on 2 February 2011, he was left out of Blackpool's 25-man squad for the remainder of the campaign. The club exercised a third year option on Clarke's contract, keeping him in the squad for the 2011\u201312 season. With first team opportunities proving limited Clarke agreed a month's loan to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in October 2011,<ref name=\"blades deal\">{{cite web|title=Blades capture duo|url=http://www.sufc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10418~2481529,00.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116172332/http://www.sufc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10418~2481529%2C00.html|archivedate=16 January 2012|publisher=Sheffield United F.C.|accessdate=14 October 2011|date=14 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> going on to make five appearances and score one goal for the [[South Yorkshire]] club.\n\n===Crawley Town===\nOn 31 January 2012, Clarke joined League Two club Crawley Town for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16816776.stm\n|title=Crawley Town sign striker Billy Clarke from Blackpool\n|publisher=BBC\n|date=31 January 2012 |accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> The signing of Clarke was seen as a signal of intent from Crawley, who beat off the interest of several other clubs. Crawley boss Steve Evans called Clarke a wonderful signing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greenscene.me/2012/01/blackpools-billy-clarke-joins-crawley-town/|title=GreenScene \u00bb Blackpool's Billy Clarke joins Crawley Town|publisher=}}</ref>\nClarke featured as a regular first team player in both 2012/2013 and 2013/2014 seasons and missed a number of games due to injury. He won Player of the Year award in the 2012/2013 season, scoring 14 goals in League 1 for Crawley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11719/8673812/crawleys-billy-clarke-has-spoken-of-his-pride-at-player-of-the-year-honour|title=Crawley's Billy Clarke has spoken of his pride at Player of the Year honour|website=Sky Sports}}</ref>\nHe scored 7 goals for Crawley in the 2013/2014 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerpunter.com/players/15746-Billy-Clarke|title=Billy Clarke - Profile and Statistics - SoccerPunter.com|website=www.soccerpunter.com}}</ref>\n\n===Bradford City===\n\nClarke signed for [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in June 2014 on a two-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk/news/2014/june/city-clinch-clarke-capture/|title=CITY CLINCH CLARKE CAPTURE - News - Bradford City|website=www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk}}</ref> He made his debut on 9 August in a 3\u20132 win against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] at [[Valley Parade]], assisting [[James Hanson (footballer born 1987)|James Hanson]]'s opening goal of the game.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28646631 \"Bradford City 3\u20132 Coventry City\"] BBC Sport. 9 August 2014. Retrieved 9 August 2014.</ref>\n\n===Charlton Athletic===\n\nClarke signed for [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] in June 2017 on a two-year deal.<ref>{{Cite news |title=DONE DEAL: Billy Clarke becomes Charlton's first summer signing |url=http://www.cafc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/charlton-athletic-football-club-new-signing-billy-clarke-3729879.aspx |publisher=Charlton Athletic Official Site |date=8 June 2017 |accessdate=8 June 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610123326/http://www.cafc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/charlton-athletic-football-club-new-signing-billy-clarke-3729879.aspx |archivedate=10 June 2017  }}</ref> He scored his first goal for Charlton in a 2-1 [[EFL Cup]] win against [[Exeter City]] on 8 August 2017.<ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40785775\n|title=Exeter 1-2 Charlton\n|publisher=BBC\n|date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref> In December 2017 Clarke suffered another serious knee injury, rupturing the anterior cruciate ligament of his left knee.\n\n===Return to Bradford===\nClarke returned to Bradford City on 31 January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk/news/2019/january/clarke-makes-city-return/|title=CLARKE MAKES CITY RETURN|website=www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk}}</ref> In May 2019, following Bradford City's relegation to League Two, it was announced that he would leave the club upon the expiry of his contract on 30 June 2019, one of 11 players to be released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/17623655.bradford-city-announce-retained-list/|title=Bradford City announce retained list|date=7 May 2019|accessdate=7 May 2019|author=Simon Parker|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> He did not find a new club for the start of the 2019\u201320 season, but trained with Bolton Wanderers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/17809492.billy-clarke-life-released-bantams/|title=Billy Clarke on life after being released by the Bantams|website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus}}</ref> In September 2019 he said that he was still looking for a new club, after the move to Bolton fell through following the departure of manager Phil Parkinson, and also said that he was missing playing.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/17916901.billy-clarke-39-s-struggle-outside-looking/|title=Billy Clarke: It's a struggle on the outside looking in|website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus}}</ref> He still worked at Bradford City as a part-time under-15s coach, two nights a week.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Plymouth Argyle===\nOn 19 October 2019, Clarke signed with League Two side [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] on a short-term deal. He made his debut that day, as an 80th minute substitute for [[George Cooper (footballer, born 1992)|George Cooper]] in a 2\u20130 win over [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]].\n\n===Grimsby Town===\n\nAfter being released by Plymouth, [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] signed Clarke on a six-month contract on 9 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/2020/january/clarke-joins-the-mariners-until-end-of-season/|title=Clarke Joins The Mariners Until End Of Season|website=Grimsby Town}}</ref>\nOn the 11 January 2020 Clarke, makes his debut for Grimsby Town FC against Leyton Orient, after coming on for Ahkeem Rose in 63rd minute, \nHe subsequently scored minutes later to make the score 1\u20130.\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 4 January 2020}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n|[[2005\u201306 Ipswich Town F.C. season|2005\u201306]]<ref name=\"soccerbase2005\">{{Soccerbase season|41447|2005|name=Billy Clarke|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref>\n|[[Football League Championship|Championship]]\n|2||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||2||0\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Ipswich Town F.C. season|2006\u201307]]<ref>{{Soccerbase season|41447|2006|name=Billy Clarke|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|27||3||4||0||1||1||0||0||32||4\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 Ipswich Town F.C. season|2007\u201308]]<ref name=\"soccerbase2007\">{{Soccerbase season|41447|2007|name=Billy Clarke|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|20||0||1||0||1||0||0||0||22||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Ipswich Town total\n!49||3||5||0||2||1||0||0||56||4\n|-\n||[[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] (loan)\n|[[2005\u201306 Colchester United F.C. season|2005\u201306]]<ref name=\"soccerbase2005\"/>\n|[[Football League One|League One]]\n|6||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||6||0\n|-\n||[[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] (loan)\n|[[2007\u201308 Falkirk F.C. season|2007\u201308]]<ref name=\"soccerbase2007\"/>\n|[[Scottish Premier League]]\n|8||1||0||0||0||0||0||0||8||1\n|-\n||[[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] (loan)\n|[[2008\u201309 Darlington F.C. season|2008\u201309]]<ref name=\"soccerbase1\">{{Soccerbase season|41447|2008|name=Billy Clarke|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref